<HEADLINE> TICAD to Note Role of Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 19 (Xinhua) -- recent regional preparatory
committee meetings for the Tokyo international conference on
African development (TICAD) have stressed the need to promote the
growth of the private sector as a driving force in Africa's
development.
</P>
<P>
Reports on the preparatory meetings held in Ouagadougou,
Burkina Faso and Windhoek, Namibia were presented at the Harare
preparatory committee meeting for TICAD ii here Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was noted that the promotion of the private sector required
capacity building in the public sector so as to improve the
business environment.
</P>
<P>
Bernadette Artivor, Director for Development Cooperation of
Namibia's National Planning Commission said, ''there was broad
agreement on the importance of the private sector as the engine
of growth and the role it plays in employment generation and
poverty alleviation as well as in enabling countries to integrate
into the global economy.''
</P>
<P>
Presenting a report of the regional workshop for eastern and
southern Africa on the TICAD ii preparatory process held in
Windhoek, Artivor said it was appropriate that private sector
development was among the priority areas of the agenda for action
for African development to be adopted in Tokyo, Japan in October,
this year.
</P>
<P>
''The objectives of ensuring a conducive environment for
private sector development and promoting investment and trade
were also endorsed,'' Artivor said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
