<HEADLINE> Cambodia's CPP Reaffirms Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian People's Party
(CPP) reaffirmed here Friday it would form a coalition government
if it wins a majority in the forthcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced after its extraordinary general
assembly, chaired by President Chea Sim and Vice-President Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
Also present were nationwide party representatives as well as
those from France and Australia, totalling 768 participants.
</P>
<P>
The meeting focused on the CPP's preparation for the upcoming
National Assembly elections, including the adoption of the party's
political statement for the election.
</P>
<P>
The party announced that the general assembly reaffirmed the
position of the CPP to form a coalition government led by one
prime minister with the participation of several political parties
in line with the constitution if the CPP wins a majority.
</P>
<P>
The assembly specifically stressed the CPP will trust Samdech
Hun Sen to form and lead the Royal Government of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
On foreign policy, it said the CPP will adhere to a policy of
peace, friendship and cooperation with all countries, especially
with neighboring countries, on the basis of equality and respect
for each other's independence, sovereignty and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
It supported the admission of the Kingdom of Cambodia into the
Association of South East Asian Nations (ASEAN) if it wins the
elections on July 28.
</P>
<P>
The party also called on the National Election Committee, the
Royal Government and all competent authorities to take appropriate
and efficient measures to ensure a safe, free, fair, transparent
and non-violent environment during the campaign period and on
polling day.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it expressed the wishes that King Norodom
Sihanouk and Queen Monineath stay in the country.
</P>
<P>
The CPP considered the presence of His Majesty an important
symbol of national unity and continuity, and he was the highest
arbitrator to ensure the normal functioning of society during the
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
