<HEADLINE> SADC Members Urged to Ratify Energy Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The 23rd Southern African
Development Community (SADC) energy ministers conference ended
here Friday, urging its members to ratify SADC's energy protocol
which will allow the formation of a commission to oversee power
issues.
</P>
<P>
Only seven of the 14-member organization, Zimbabwe, Angola,
Botswana, Lesotho, Mauritius, Namibia and Swaziland have ratified
the protocol which has been on the cards since June last year.
</P>
<P>
Countries that still have to ratify the protocol are new
comers Democratic Republic of Congo and Seychelles as well as
South Africa, Malawi, Tanzania, Zambia and Mozambique, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministers noted that in view of the slow ratification of
the energy protocol, the establishment of the SADC Energy
Commission was not progressing as expected because of lack of a
quorum.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also discussed the region's Angolan-based
Petroleum Training Center which has been set up to provide
further training on the energy sector and the upstream and
downstream sectors of the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the SADC training program on rural energy
planning and environmental management and agreed more still has
to be done for capacity building in rural energy planning.
</P>
<P>
The ministers noted that the activities of the Southern
African Power Pool (SAPP) through its interconnected network that
supplies power to the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The network has currently been affected by problems of
reliability particularly blackouts and power failures caused by
oscillations in the operation of the Matimba-Insukamini and
Mozambique-Zimbabwe interconnections.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed and adopted the African Solar Program
(1996-2005).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing session of the conference, Zimbabwe's
Transport and Energy Minister Enos Chikowore stressed the
importance of regional cooperation in the energy sector, saying
that this is crucial to the overall economic growth of the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
