<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Have Clinical Trial on Anti-AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Clinical trials on the
purported anti-AIDS drug Virodene P058 are set to begin in the
near future, a spokesman for Virodene Pharmaceutical Holdings
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Larry Heidebrecht said the company would submit a protocol to
the Medicines Control Council (MCC) detailing tests to establish
the absorption rate of the drug from skin patches.
</P>
<P>
He said he expected these "pre-tests", to be performed on
healthy volunteers, would take place in the next few weeks, once
a committee of the MCC approved the protocol.
</P>
<P>
Once the absorption rate tests had been complete, preparations
for a full clinical trial on HIV sufferers would begin, he said.
</P>
<P>
The absorption rate tests would not take long to complete and
would be conducted by a professional laboratory, which would meet
the requirements of the MCC, Heidebrecht said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier research on the drug was condemned by the MCC as being
unprofessional. However, Heidebrecht said a good working
relationship with the MCC had since been established.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association Friday quoted unidentified
sources as reporting that a consortium of black-owned business
had bought a majority share in the company which owns the rights
to Virodene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
