<HEADLINE> Angola: 2,500 Die of AIDS Over Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,500 Angolans have died
from AIDS till March, 1998 in the past decade, Deputy Minister of
Health Teresa Cohen said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Teresa disclosed this to reporters at the airport when she
returned from the conference of health ministers in Africa on the
spreading of AIDS in the region, which was held in Egypt from
June 13 to 17.
</P>
<P>
She said that since the first case of AIDS was diagnosed in
1985, more than 250,000 people have been tested HIV positive and
over 2,500 HIV infected have died from the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
Ever since 1985, the number of people who were diagnosed HIV
positive has been rising, Teresa noted, adding that the actual
AIDS cases may have exceeded 250,000 because the general
investigation of it was unable to reach every province in the
war-ravaged southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said at the conference, delegates from
African countries held in-depth discussion about the spreading of
AIDS in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting urged each and every African country to adopt an
integrated national anti-AIDS plan in a bid to more effectively
curb the spreading of the killing disease.
</P>
<P>
Teresa considered that as in the case of anti-malaria, it is
not enough to fight AIDS only by efforts of the health authority
in each country.
</P>
<P>
The spreading of AIDS can be contained only with the concerted
efforts of all walks of life in the whole society, said the
deputy minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
