<HEADLINE> Lesotho King Vows to Help Unemployed Miners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho King Letsie III said
Friday that his country would take new measures to help mine
workers retrenched from South African mines.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the first session of Lesotho's fifth
parliament in Maseru, Letsie III said Lesotho should look at the
exploitation of its own mineral resources as an alternative for
the retrenched workers.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho, totally surrounded by South Africa, has more than
100,000 people working in South African mines.
</P>
<P>
Letsie said investigations were underway to establish a
large-scale diamond mining venture at Liqhobong in Lesotho's
northeastern highlands.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from the Lesotho Highlands Water Project should also
be used to address poverty, provide jobs and develop
infrastructure, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another possibility in the job creation and poverty
alleviation thrust was expansion of the manufacturing and
agricultural industries.
</P>
<P>
"The pipeline of industrial projects under implementation
includes the first integrated textile and clothing project to be
implemented by the Lesotho National Development Corporation. This
project alone will created about 900 jobs," Letsie said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
