<HEADLINE> IPE, Nord Pool Forge European Energy Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 19 (Xinhua) - The International Petroleum Exchange
(IPE) and Nord Pool announced Friday a major co-operation
agreement, enabling users of each market to access the contracts
listed by both exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The alliance of Europe's two largest energy futures exchanges
is motivated by the wish to ensure the best possible service to
members and users of both exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between the two exchanges is designed to ensure
that companies and individuals operating within the European
energy and futures industries can have the widest possible choice
among exchange-traded products.
</P>
<P>
The IPE and Nord Pool believe that market participants are
interested in the products and contracts that can be traded,
rather than those in the individual exchange that provides them.
</P>
<P>
The IPE is Europe's largest energy futures and options
exchange, offering contracts in Brent Curde, Gas Oil and Natural
Gas.
</P>
<P>
Nord Pool is the world's first multinational power exchange,
with contracts in electricity for the spot and futures of the
power markets in the Nordic countries.
</P>
<P>
IPE chief executive Lynton Jones said: "We are always looking
to cooperate and share expertise with other exchanges. Nord Pool,
with its expertise and leading position in the electricity sector,
is a particularly attractive partner for the IPE."
</P>
<P>
"We hope that this agreement will create new opportunities for
our members, grow our business and ultimately improve the risk
management tools available for the energy industry in general," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
