<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PTA Bank Needs Large Sum for Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Preferential Trade Area (PTA)
Bank needs about 50 billion U.S. Dollars to assist the newly
privatized state-owned firms in member countries.
</P>
<P>
Cassim Chilumpha, the PTA Bank Chairman for Board of Governors
and Malawian Minister of Finance, disclosed this at a press
briefing jointly held with the visiting PTA Bank President Martin
Ogang in Blantyre Thursday, the Malawi News Agency (MANA)
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bank intends to acquire the money through borrowing from
international money markets and members, Chilumpha said, adding
that non-members of the bank but within the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) grouping are asked to pledge
for their support and guarantees.
</P>
<P>
"As most of the member countries are at the moment trying to
distance themselves from business ventures as evidenced by the
divestiture of state-owned corporations, there is high demand for
investment capital among business entrepreneurs and we feel the
bank is the best organization which can give assistance," said
Chilumpha.
</P>
<P>
He added that South Africa which stands to benefit more from
the privatization process in the region as most of the raw
materials used by the manufacturing industries are procured from
that country "should feel compelled to come to the rescue."
</P>
<P>
"It is very unfair for South Africa to continue enjoying the
business monopoly with countries of COMESA while continuing to be
a non-member," he said, adding that he and the president of the
bank have already briefed the current Chairman of COMESA
President Frederick Chiluba of Zambia to hold talks with
President Nelson Mandela of South Africa on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that PTA's banks corporate plans which were
presented to Malawian President Bakili Muluzi also seek ways of
encouraging member countries of COMESA to join the PTA Bank.
</P>
<P>
"In so doing, the bank's bargaining power for soliciting loans
for the emerging private sector will be strengthened," said
Chilumpha.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, he observed, members will not be asked to pay
additional money apart from their usual contributions.
</P>
<P>
"What the bank needs is their pledged support," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our traditional donors like the U.S.A, the United Kingdom,
Japan, India and others will also be asked to come in," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Ogang said that the bank's investment capital is
between four to five hundred million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to reach a capital of five billion U.S. Dollars by
the next millennium," he added.
</P>
<P>
The PTA Bank's overall funding to Malawi's projects and
business loans currently stands at 41 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
