<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Sends Letter to Annan on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has sent a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
renewing a proposal on demilitarizing Cyprus, government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Clerides sent the letter to the U.N. chief on Thursday with the
aim of reactivating the proposal on demilitarizing the divided
Mediterranean island, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides declined to divulge the details of the letter, but
adding that the Cypriot president demanded not only Britain, which
is a guarantor power of Cyprus, but also the U.N. Security Council
and the international community to undertake their
responsibilities to restore peace in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Clerides first raised the demilitarization proposal in December
1993, calling for the disbandment of Greek Cypriot National
Guard and Turkish Cypriot armed forces, as well as the withdrawal
of Turkish forces from northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, the weapons should be confiscated and
transferred into the U.N. peacekeeping forces' custody and the
money saved through demilitarization should be deposited into a
fund to benefit the two communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
"The Cyprus government has practically proved with specific
suggestions that it is in favor of reducing the tension, but
unfortunately we have not had any response from the other side,"
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz's statement
that he intends to deliberate with Britain on the issue,
Stylianides said "it is absurd that a country which violated the
Treaty of Guarantee and the constitutional order which it should
have defended, to appear now as a guarantor, quote the treaty and
ask another guarantor power to help her reduce the tension."
</P>
<P>
He accused "the Turkish occupation force" of continuing to
violate international law and create all kinds of tension in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides defended the recent landing of Greek warplanes at
the Paphos military air base, saying it was a scheduled routine
exercise, and part of the joint defense pact between Cyprus and
Greece. He said this should not have been considered a provocation
because defense is Cyprus' sovereign right.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece signed a joint defense pact in November
1993, under which Greece will provide military assistance if
Cyprus is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Turkey sent six F-16 fighters to the Turkish
Cypriot-controlled northern Cyprus Thursday in retaliation for the
landing of six Greek warplanes at the Paphos base in the Greek
Cypriot-controlled south earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Five Turkish navy warships also visited Wednesday the ports of
Kyrenia and Famagusta in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in 1974
after a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both North Atlantic Treaty Organization
allies, have long been at odds over this strategic island, where
tension has been running high since January last year when Cyprus
ordered Russian-made anti-aircraft missiles which are scheduled to
be delivered later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
