<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO's New Approach to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The African regional office of the
World Health Organization (WHO) said Friday it has decided to
adopt a three-pronged initiative to curb the high HIV/AIDS
mortality and morbidity rates in the region.
</P>
<P>
The initiative is mobilization of Africa's political
leadership, including heads of state, in the anti-AIDS campaign
and the institution on more effective intervention strategies, a
statement from the WHO office in Nigeria said.
</P>
<P>
The third strand of the approach is strengthening of
cooperative and collaborative efforts among its partners, the WHO
headquarters and UNAIDS, to make maximum use of available
resources with the view to making greater impact in the overall
containment endeavor.
</P>
<P>
Ebrahim Samba, WHO regional director for Africa, called on all
member states of the WHO Africa region to embrace the new
initiative which will strengthen the capacity of national health
authorities to adopt policies and promote practices that offer
better opportunity for monitoring the disease situation.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Africa, with only 10 percent of the
world's population, currently had 70 percent of the 20.8 million
global cases of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Every country on the continent has, to lesser or larger
degree, reported cases of HIV/AIDS which every day infects 7,500
Africans out of the global total of 16,000 daily infections.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of 1997, close to nine million adults, divided
equally between men and women, and 1.5 million children born with
HIV infection, developed AIDS in the region. Of this, about seven
million children and adults have died," it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the most vulnerable groups had been
from Africa's productive people between the ago of 15 and 40,
resulting in weakening the productive base, a growing orphan
population, further strains on already under-staffed and
under-funded health services across the continent.
</P>
<P>
Factors accounting for the grim situation, it said, included
the wide practice of unprotected sex, high fertility, high
incidence of sexually transmitted diseases and poor access to
care and information.
</P>
<P>
The organization said that efforts made so far to contain the
pandemic included caring for the victims and launching and
promotion of sensitization campaigns on safe sex through the use
of condoms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
