<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Progress in Mediation of Ethio-Eritrean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) said Friday that it has made no progress in its
efforts to mediate in the Ethio-Eritrean border dispute.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing here, OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed
Salim told reporters that the OAU delegation of heads of states
to Ethiopia and Eritrea Thursday morning held a meeting with
Ethiopian Premier Meles Zenawi and then proceeded to Asmara where
it met with Eritrean President Isaias Afewerki.
</P>
<P>
The delegation had another meeting Friday morning with Prime
Minister Meles but made no meaningful progress.
</P>
<P>
Salim said: "In the course of its discussions with both
parties, the Ethiopian side reiterated its acceptance of the
proposals of the facilitators. The Eritrean side stated clearly
that the facilitation was over."
</P>
<P>
"From this point of view, therefore, the delegation was not
able at this juncture to make headway with respect to the
facilitators recommendations," Salim told the journalists.
</P>
<P>
Salim said that "OAU will nonetheless continue with its
efforts."
</P>
<P>
"The issue is too serious and grave and deserve the continued
attention of the organization," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The OAU delegation continues therefore to be seized with the
matter," Salim said, adding that "it will continue with its
efforts at the levels of ambassadors of the members of the
delegation, ministers and heads of states."
</P>
<P>
He said the OAU delegation will seek the cooperation of both
parties to help them reach a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
"The OAU delegation urged both parties to continue exercise
maximum restraint and avoid taking any action which could
escalate the tension and further harm the future relations
between the two countries," Salim said.
</P>
<P>
The OAU high-level delegation was led by current Chairman of
the OAU and President Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso, and it
includes President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, President Pasteur
Bizimungu of Rwanda, Minister of Foreign Affairs of Djibouti
Mohamed Mousa Shehim and OAU Secretary-General Salim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
