<HEADLINE> Israeli Lawmaker Urges Demolishing Goldstein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli opposition
lawmaker on Friday urged the army to demolish the memorials built
for Baruch Goldstein, a Jewish extremist who massacred 29 Muslim
worshippers in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Raanan
Cohen, secretary general of the leading opposition Labor Party,
said that the army should take immediate actions to uproot the
memorials for Goldstein built in the Kiryat Arba settlement near
the flashpoint West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Cohen noted that the Knesset (Parliament) already approved a
bill early this month, banning memorials for those who committed
acts of terror. So, he added, it was not necessary for the army to
negotiate with Goldstein's family before carrying out a demolition.
</P>
<P>
The newly-passed bill, popularly known as the Goldstein Law,
went into effect on Thursday. It requested the defense minister to
order the army to demolish the memorials for Goldstein in Kiryat
Arba.
</P>
<P>
Goldstein gunned down 29 Muslim worshippers in early 1994 inside
the Ibrahim Mosque (Tomb of the Patriarchs called by Jews) in
central Hebron before being beaten to death by angry Arabs. He was
later buried in the nearby settlement Kiryat Arba.
</P>
<P>
Jewish extremists have turned the Goldstein grave into a
pilgrim site to express their anti-Arab views. A plaza has been
paved around the gravesite and is decorated with memorial candles,
a cupboard for holy books, a bench and water taps.
</P>
<P>
Israeli peace activists and leftist politicians have been
lobbying the government to relocate Goldstein's tomb in order to
prevent extremists from provoking violent clashes with
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
