<HEADLINE> Security Council Authorizes Iraq to Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of the
United Nations on Friday adopted a resolution which authorized
Iraq to import 300 million U.S. dollars worth of oil equipment and
spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The move aims to upgrade Iraq's capacity of oil export. The
Security Council adopted a resolution in February which allowed
Iraq to export 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over every
six months in order to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies for its people. Without the needed equipment and spare
parts, Iraq cannot reach the new target.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since it invaded Kwait in
1990. The Security Council in 1995 adopted Resolution 986 which
allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every
six months to ease the humanitarian crisis in the country caused
by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has reiterated that the present stage of oil-for-food
program should be the last one Iraq has to accept. It wants a
complete lifting of the sanctions in six months because it said it
has destroyed all its prohibited weapons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
