<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Protect Turkish Cypriots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Amid tension between Ankara and
Athens in Cyprus, Turkey reiterated Friday its determination to
protect Turkish Cypriots in the northern part of the divided
island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in the Aegean city of Izmir, Sukru Sina
Gurel, state minister for European and Cyprus affairs, said that
Turkey has rights and duties to maintain peace in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We have to show Greece that it would be given the necessary
response if it made plans to base its air forces in Cyprus, and
we did so," Gurel said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's six F-16 fighters flew to northern Cyprus Thursday
morning in response to the landing of four F-16 fighters
and two C-130 transport planes at an air base near the western
coastal town of Paphos on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish warplanes, after an overnight stay, Friday left the
Turkish Cypriot-controlled areas for their base in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"If anybody is still curious to know what more Turkey can do
to protect the security of the Turkish Cypriots, we can show them
this as well," Gurel said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Turkish official stressed that Turkey has no
intention of escalating the tension on the island of Cyprus and
desires no heated confrontation with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Following Tuesday's landing of Greek warplanes in Cyprus,
Turkish government officials accused Greece of attempting to
Hellenize the divided island, calling it "a provocative action."
</P>
<P>
However, Greek Deputy Foreign Minister Yorgo Papandreou said
in Athens Friday that Turkey escalated the tension on the island
because "it was disappointed with the results of EU's Cardiff
summit."
</P>
<P>
He rejected the suggestions that the current tension would
lead to a war between the two foes.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared the "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which is recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The latest tension between the arch-rivals of Turkey and
Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization,
prompted grave concern among their Western allies.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain, France and Germany have called on
the two neighbors to refrain from taking further steps in order
not to make the situation in Cyprus more complicated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
