<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Japan Pledges not to Delay Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Friday that he was not sure whether Japan could implement
major financial reforms before its July parliamentary elections,
but that Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had pledged not
to delay them.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not in a position to know whether they can do that,"
Clinton told reporters before a meeting with economic advisers.
But he said Hashimoto had pledged in a telephone call on Tuesday
night to act in a "timely fashion."
</P>
<P>
"He said to me they were prepared to issue a statement which
would be clear and specific about what they intended to do in a
timely fashion," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
But "he did not say whether it would be before or just after
the parliamentary elections, but he said he would not delay
about it," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he had told Hashimoto that the United States
wants to support the Japanese economic recovery because it has a
great stake in it, "but no short-term efforts would work unless
there was a serious long-term, very comprehensive commitment to
economic reform."
</P>
<P>
The United States took part in a rare intervention to prop up
the sagging yen on Wednesday after Hashimoto promised to act
boldly to revive its economy through reforms.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official said on Friday in Washington the United States
recognized that Hashimoto may need to do some political
"balancing", and that some elements of the reform package may be
accomplished before the Upper House elections and other after
the elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers,
on a whirlwind emergency visit to Japan, said on Friday that
Tokyo should pull its act together in the next three weeks --
before the parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
And a U.S. official in Tokyo said on Friday that Washington
would be closely watching for a "sense of direction" on the
reforms before July 12 when the elections will be held. 
</P>
