<HEADLINE> Simitis Accuses Turkey of Creating Tension in Aegean Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
Friday accused neighboring Turkey of creating the recent tension
in the Aegean Sea, saying that Greek warplanes's landing on the
divided island republic had nothing to do with the tension.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a cabinet meeting, Simitis said the four Greek F-16
jet fighters and a C-130 transport plane flew Tuesday to Cyprus'
Paphos air base at the invitation of the Cyprus government, the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
While accusing Greece of escalating tension in the Aegean by
landing its warplanes in Cyprus, Turkey in turn sent six F-16
fighters to the Gecitkale air base in northern Cyprus on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos also stressed Friday
that it was the Cyprus government's inalienable right to grant
permission for brief visits by Greek military planes within the
framework of the training policy followed by Greece and Cyprus as
part of their joint defense doctrine.
</P>
<P>
He warned that it would do Turkey no good to use the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
The United States has called on both Greece and Turkey to find
ways to reduce the tension in the Aegean. To show its interest in
the peace of the region, the U.S. aircraft carrier "Eisenhower"
will visit Greece.  
</P>
</TEXT>
