<HEADLINE> FM: Cyprus not Intended to Create Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Defending the recent arrival of
Greek warplanes, Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides
said here Friday that Cyprus is intended to neither create tension
nor provoke anyone.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting of the Foreign Affairs
Committee at the House of Representatives, Kasoulides said the four
Greek F-16 fighters, which arrived Tuesday in the Greek
Cypriot-controlled south, were only on a training mission
scheduled a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides affirmed that the Cypriot government does not intend
to play games, pledging that no more Greek warplanes will arrive
here this summer before the annual "Nikiforos" military manoeuvre,
due to take place in October.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister accused Turkey of creating an "artificial
tension," adding that "it is advisable that we are aware of the
intentions and respond accordingly."
</P>
<P>
The Greek warplanes' landing in the south has angered Turkey,
who accused Greece of escalating tension on the divided island and
sent Thursday six F-16 fighters to the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been mounting since early last year when Cyprus
ordered the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, which are
due to be delivered later this year. Turkey has threatened to use
all means to block the deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since Turkish troops landed and
took over the northern third of the island in 1974 following a
failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on press reports on the movement of U.S. Carrier
"Eisenhower" toward the Mediterranean Sea, Kasoulides said he has
received assurances from the U.S. Embassy here that the carrier is
not heading to Cyprus as reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
It is heading to the eastern Mediterranean Sea because of the
Kosovo crisis in Yugoslavia, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
