<HEADLINE> San Francisco Extends Smoking Ban to Park Playgrounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A new policy has made San
Francisco one of the few cities in the United States to outlaw
outdoor smoking.
</P>
<P>
The city's Recreation and Park Commission Thursday approved the
policy to ban smoking at public parks and recreation centers
frequented by thousands of children.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the ban is a way to keep children from
becoming addicted to smoking. The 29 parks where smoking will be
prohibited are small and mainly used by children.
</P>
<P>
The policy will be enforced in two to three weeks, once signs
are posted at playgrounds. Officials said that smoking in public
parks is not illegal, but parks department staff will enforce the
ban by telling people they can't smoke. There is no monetary fine
if someone is caught smoking.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the year, California banned smoking in bars and
nightclubs, smokers' last public indoor refuge. San Francisco's
new measure is the latest attack on outdoor smoking. Other cities
have banned smoking in public lines for movies and buses, or in
public gardens, outdoor courtyards and near children's play areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
