<HEADLINE> Philadelphia to Crack Down on Gun Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Philadephia Mayor Edward G.
Rendell and the National Rifle Association (NRA) have agreed to
join efforts to seek federal money for cracking down on gun
violence, according to The Philadelphia Inquirer Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wayne LaPierre, the NRA chief executive officer, said Thursday
that his organization would lobby with the Republican leadership
in Congress to give Philadelphia money to make it a "test city."
</P>
<P>
NRA President Charlton Heston first came up with the idea at
the group's recent convention, asking President Bill Clinton to
designate one city for zero tolerance of gun violence. The idea is
to prove the NRA's view that lack of enforcement of existing gun
laws lies at the root of gun violence, not a lack of gun-control
laws.
</P>
<P>
On NBC-TV's "Meet the Press" Sunday, Heston talked up a program
in Richmond, Virginia, that has cut murders in half, saying, "We
would like to do that in Philadelphia."
</P>
<P>
LaPierre urged Rendell to lobby President Clinton for the
program.
</P>
<P>
"If he'll get the White House, I've got Congress," LaPierre
said.
</P>
<P>
Rendell had continued his efforts to pressure gunmakers to take
steps to curb sales to criminals. On Sunday in Reno, Nevada, at
the annual meeting of the U.S. Conference of Mayors, Rendell is
scheduled to make the case for gun control, such as limiting
buyers to one gun a month.
</P>
<P>
The mayor will discuss the issue before 300 mayors in a forum
with the head of the gunmakers' trade organization.
</P>
<P>
Among major U.S. cities, Philadelphia has the highest
proportion of murders and robberies committed by gun. Last year, a
record 82 percent of 409 homicides were by firearms. By contrast,
the rate in New York was 62 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
