<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Friday that he was not sure whether Japan could implement major
financial reforms before its July parliamentary elections, but
that Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had pledged not to
delay them.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not in a position to know whether they can do that,"
Clinton told reporters before a meeting with economic advisers.
But he said Hashimoto had pledged in a telephone call Tuesday
night to act in a "timely fashion."
</P>
<P>
"He said to me they were prepared to issue a statement which
would be clear and specific about what they intended to do in a
timely fashion," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
But "he did not say whether it would be before or just after
the parliamentary elections, but he said he would not delay about
it," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he had told Hashimoto that the United States
wanted to support the Japanese economic recovery because it had a
great stake in it, "but no short-term efforts would work unless
there was a serious long-term, very comprehensive commitment to
economic reform."
</P>
<P>
The United States took part in a rare intervention to prop up
the sagging yen Wednesday after Hashimoto promised to act boldly
to revive its economy through reforms.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official said Friday in Washington the United States
recognized that Hashimoto might need to do some political
"balancing" and that some elements of the reform package might be
accomplished before the Upper House elections and other after the
elections.
</P>
<P>
