and the U.S. delegation led by Summers was to discuss the
seriousness of Japan's economic problems and how to nurse its sick
banking system back to health.
</P>
<P>
He said Japan should take concrete steps to fix its ailing
economy, saying, "The key now is for them to act and act
effectively." He said the mountain of bad debts hanging over
Japan's banking system was the most immediate and pressing problem
for Tokyo to tackle.
</P>
<P>
And a U.S. official in Tokyo said Friday that Washington would
be closely watching for a "sense of direction" on the reforms
before July 12 when the elections will be held. 
