<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Second Annual ESAF Loan for Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Friday announced the approval of the second annual loan
under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) for the
former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia in an amount of 24 million
U.S. dollars equivalent.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to support the government's economic
program for 1998/99. The loan is available in two equal semiannual
installments, the first of which is available this month.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 program supported by the ESAF aims real GDP growth of
5 percent, end-year inflation of 3 percent, and a current account
deficit of 7.3 percent of GDP. Consistent with these goals, the
overall fiscal deficit in 1998 is projected to increase only
slightly to 0.7 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting member
countries that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payments. ESAF loans carry an interest
rate of 0.5 percent a year and are repayable over 10 years with a
5.5 year grace period.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia succeeded the former Socialist Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia to membership in the IMF in December 1992. Its quota is
some 67 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF credit
totals about 87 million dollars equivalent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
