<HEADLINE> U.N. Committee to Review Discrimination Against Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Committee on the
Elimination of Discrimination against Women will review the
situation in a number of countries in its forthcoming session, the
U.N. General Assembly announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The countries bound to submit their reports on women's status
to the meeting scheduled for June 22-July 10 are New Zealand,
Nigeria, Panama, Peru, the Republic of Korea, Slovakia, South
Africa and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa's report says the country has a high rate of all
forms of violent crime, partly due to the state of conflict and
deprivation from which the country emerged," a U.N. background
release said.
</P>
<P>
"While state violence has decreased since the country's 1994
political transformation, rates of reported rape, sexual abuse of
children and domestic violence are increasing," it said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 161 countries have ratified or acceded to the
Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination
against Women which was adopted by the General Assembly in 1979
and came into force in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Convention parties are committed to submit national reports on
measures taken to comply with their treaty obligations, with an
initial report required within one year of accession, and periodic
reports at least every four years.
</P>
<P>
The committee reviews the reports, evaluates the progress and
formulates recommendations to all states parties on eliminating
discrimination against women.
</P>
<P>
These cover issues such as the impact of structural adjustment
policies, maternity leave, violence against women and the
dissemination of the convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0050 </DOCNO>
