<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM: Cyprus Impossible to Become Greek Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 19 (Xinhua) -- It is impossible that Cyprus
becomes entirely a Greek island, as long as there is a Turkish
republic, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said Thursday
afternoon at the end of his two-day visit to Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said, "Turkey wants a right and just solution to the
situation in Cyprus and is ready to cooperate as before." "Its
first condition will be to give up the idea of transforming Cyprus
into a Greek island and the Turkish community into a minority," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"Greece would be better advised not to try Turkey for size,"
the Turkish prime minister warned, adding that Turkey did not wait
for anybody's mediation.
</P>
<P>
Tension is aggravating recently in Cyprus, as Turkey sent six
F-16 fighters Thursday to the northern part of Cyprus in response
to the landing of four Greek F-16s and two C-130 transport planes
in the southern Cypriot air base Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the small island in the
aftermath of a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 35,000 to 50,000 Turkish troops are stationed
in the northern part of Cyprus with a claimed aim to protect
Turkish Cypriots who unilaterally declared the Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus, now recognized only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
