<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Contributes to Asian Financial Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Financial officials from 17
countries and regions lauded China for its contribution in helping
maintain financial stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The praise is contained in a joint statement compiled by the
financial officials from the Group of Seven (G-7) major
industrialized countries and 10 Asia-Pacific economies in Tokyo
for a one-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
They welcomed China's reiteration of its firm commitment to
maintain the stability of its currency and said the Renminbi has
helped defend the stability of Asian economies and financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
China has been under pressure to devalue their currency as the
Japanese yen and various Asian currencies weaken and threaten to
erode the international competitiveness of Chinese exports.
</P>
<P>
The conference participants also appealed to Japan to correct
its bad loan ridden banking system in order to put its slumping
economy back on the road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
"It is of vital importance to Japan, to the recovery of Asia,
and to the entire world economy that Japan restore its banking
system to health, achieve domestic demand-led growth, and to open
and deregulate its markets," they said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the participants commended Japan and the United
States for their recent joint action in the currency markets to
buoy the sagging yen.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the G-7 and the Asia-Pacific economies was
attended by officials from Australia, China, Hong Kong, Indonesia,
Malaysia, New Zealand, the Philippines, Singapore, South Korea and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank also sent delegates to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 group consists of Britain, Canada, France, Germany,
Italy, Japan and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
