<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf on
Saturday said frequent exchange of visits by officials between
Iran and Iraq is very important to improve the bilateral
relations, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A closer contact will help reduce the differences of the two
countries and pave way for normalizing the bilateral relations,
al-Sahhaf said during a meeting with Abdullah Najafi, head of an
Iranian committee for the prisoners and the missing in war.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the need to make joint efforts to settle the
remaining issues of prisoners of war (POW) and the missing in
action (MIA) as soon as possible. (Iraq-Iran-Closer Contact)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his
Indian counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee will have an important
meeting on fringes of the forthcoming SAARC summit in Colombo,
capital of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
During their bilateral meeting at Colombo, the two leaders "can
send their Foreign Secretaries back to the negotiating table,"
said a Foreign Office spokesman at a weekly briefing here Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The 10th summit meeting of the seven-nation South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) is scheduled to be
held in Colombo late July. (Pak-India-PM)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Deputies of the finance ministers and central bank
governors from eighteen countries and regions are holding an
emergency meeting in Tokyo on Saturday to seek ways to stabilize
international currencies.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting is expected to issue a statement showing
the participants' willingness to cooperate in stabilizing global
currency markets.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the meeting will reconfirm the necessity to
rectify the excessive depreciation of the Japanese yen against the
U.S. dollar, following the recent joint intervention by Japan and
the United States. (Japan-Currency-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
troika and the Friends of Cambodia (FOC) are satisfied with the
preparations for the Cambodian elections scheduled for July 26,
the Troika's top diplomats said here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the satisfaction at a press conference right
after a meeting between the ASEAN Troika, consisting of Thailand,
Indonesia and the Philippines, and the Friends of Cambodia, namely
Australia, Canada, the United States, the European Union and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon read a troika
statement, saying the three countries support the important role
of Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk in helping restore the
country's political stability, especially his call Wednesday on
the Cambodian people to exercise their right to vote without
fear. (Thailand-Cambodia-ASEAN) 
