<HEADLINE> Bulgarians never Hostile to Serbians: Stoyanov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- President Petar Stoyanov said
Bulgarians and Serbians live in harmony and are never hostile to
each other, a Yugoslav weekly reported.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov's comments came as the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is threatening to take military action against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Bulgaria is closely watching the situation in Kosovo, but
Bulgaria does not want to become a political hostage over the
incidents occurring on Yugoslav soil," the exclusive interview by
the Nin weekly quoted Stoyanov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Regarding economic sanctions imposed on Yugoslavia by Western
countries, the president said although Bulgaria favors the
measures taken by the international community, it did not propose
sanctions against Yugoslavia on its own initiative.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, Stoyanov said such sanctions would inflict
suffering on Bulgaria from the economic losses incurred.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria is in a dilemma on the Kosovo issue. On the one hand,
Bulgaria fears its "offense" to Yugoslavia will influence the
long-term relations between the two countries. On the other hand,
Bulgaria has no choice but to "approve" of the measures taken by
NATO and the European Union (EU) against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
