<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Unveil 20 Energy Projects to International Tenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 20 (Xinhua) -- In defiance of the U.S. call for no
big investment in Iran's energy sector, Tehran Saturday invited
international tenders for 20 huge oil and gas projects.
</P>
<P>
The projects, worth 8 billion U.S. dollars, will be tendered
for on a buy-back basis in the current Iranian year starting from
March 21, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., accusing Iran of allegedly supporting terrorism, has
threatened to punish any company which has an investment of more
than 20 million dollars in the energy sector of Iran.
</P>
<P>
But the d'Amato law signed by U.S. President Bill Clinton in
1996 to this effect has met strong opposition in the world.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure particularly from Europe, Clinton announced a
month ago not to impose sanction on three French, Russian and
Malaysian companies for concluding a contract of 2 billion dollars
to develop an Iranian gas field. Iran hailed it as a victory.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the tender plan, Iranian Deputy Oil Minister Mehdi
Husseini was quoted by the radio as saying that the projects will
be implemented in a period of three to five years according to
different contracts with foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said the projects are aimed at raising
Iran's oil production capacity by 1.4 million barrels per day
(bpd) and annual gas production capacity by 70 million cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
Iran's oil production capacity stands at 4 million bpd and it
produced 3.925 million bpd at the beginning of this Iranian year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
