<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Regrets U.S. Sanction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan said on Saturday that
it regretted economic sanctions imposed by the United States as a
result of its nuclear blasts, but insisted on safeguarding its
national interests in its own way.
</P>
<P>
Washington slapped a string of sanctions on Pakistan and its
neighbor India on Thursday, including bans on aid and on support
for loans from international financial institutions, but stopped
short of a humanitarian aid embargo.
</P>
<P>
The move came in response to the five underground nuclear tests
conducted on May 11 and 13 by India, in defiance of the great
concern of the international community, and the nuclear tests by
Pakistan late that month.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. action does not take into account the perilous threat
to our security as a result of the Indian nuclear tests," a
foreign office spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We have chosen the path of self-reliance. We will
single-mindedly pursue what we deem is necessary to safeguard our
security, independence and territorial integrity and national
interests," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan refused any unilateral prescription recommended by the
international community, he said.
</P>
<P>
"No one should expect Pakistan to accept, much less implement,
prescriptions determined by a state or group of states
unilaterally," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"A uni-dimensional pursuit of the goal of non-proliferation,
especially its application to a nuclearized South Asia, is
self-defeating," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman confirmed that the prime ministers of Pakistan
and India would meet in Colombo, Sri Lanka, late next month on the
sidelines of the summit meeting of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
