<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Busy Looking For More Customers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese banks, which now face
stiffer competition, are finding themselves 'condescending' to
look for more promising customers and 'marry' profitable
companies, marking a shift to a buyer's market.
</P>
<P>
The Fujian Branch of the Industrial and Commercial Bank of
China recently signed cooperation agreements with ten of the most
prosperous enterprises in Fujian, promising more convenient and
efficient service, in return for agreements to keep the companies'
money in the bank and pay off loans on time.
</P>
<P>
Such practices were not common in the past, because the
Industrial and Commercial bank of China and the three other
state-owned specialized banks -- the Construction Bank of China,
Bank of China, and the Agricultural Bank of China -- were the 'big
four' in banking and cared little about the actual needs of
companies.
</P>
<P>
Under the central planning system, banks loaned money where the
government told them to, a system that was rife with favoritism
and incompetence, resulting in a large number of bad loans and
poor money circulation.
</P>
<P>
But, China's financial reforms called for the 'big four' to
become genuine commercial banks after 1994, putting them on an
equal footing with their new counterparts, like the Shenzhen
Development Bank and China Investment Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Busy Looking For Customers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Banks are now responsible for their own profit and loss
statement, with the central bank, the People's Bank of China,
exercising a certain amount of supervision. So now, every bank
tries every means possible to attract promising customers to gain
an edge over the competition.
</P>
<P>
Banks in Beijing are also vying for such big and profitable
clients as the Yanshan Petrochemical Corporation, and enterprises
are choosing banks according to the services provided, local
sources say.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, banks are trying to attract individual customers
by providing various financial services from housing consultation
to stock and foreign exchange trading. And, the practice is
growing more popular nationwide, a central bank official says.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that this is the natural result of China's
reforms in finances and enterprises and is good for the
commercialization of state banks and a modern management system.
</P>
<P>
As for the customers themselves, the improved service has
increased the use of financial services and financial awareness,
which drives China's market and economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
