<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanctions to Hurt India: U.S. Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to India Richard
F. Celeste has said that American sanctions would hurt India by
undermining investors' confidence for future projects and might
even lead to withdrawal of existing investment.
</P>
<P>
In an interview to India's magazine "Outlook," which made it
public here Saturday, Celeste said that the real impact was as
much indirect as it was direct. It would make those confronting
important investment decisions think twice about whether this was
where they wanted to put their money now.
</P>
<P>
The United States Thursday announced its detailed sanctions
imposed on India in the wake of its conducting of five successive
underground nuclear tests on May 11 and 13. The sanctions could
hit direct flow of over 2.5 billion U.S. dollars this year to
India.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from India finding it hard to arrange financing for big
projects, there would also be withdrawal of some foreign
institutional investment from the Indian market," Celeste said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Japanese and European financial institutions would
also put up a go slow sign, he further said.
</P>
<P>
Celeste urged India to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT), saying that India's self-imposed moratorium on testing was
not enough. 
</P>
</TEXT>
