<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Missile Expert on Commercial Launch Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The assertion that "China
used U.S. know-how to improve its nuclear ballistic missiles" is
simply untrue, Zhang Xinxia, president of the China Great Wall
Industry Corporation (CGWIC), said at a press conference here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, a decision and policy maker for China's commercial
launch services, hoped the people of the United States would
become supportive of the normal, commercial launch services
provided by China for U.S. satellites after learning the facts.
</P>
<P>
It is due to the ignorance of the development of China's Long
March launch vehicles that some Americans think China's 10
successful launches in the past two years were the result of
U.S. assistance, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Long March launches were successful before 1985
when China first offered commercial services to foreign clients,
said Zhang, a 1968 graduate of the University of Aeronautics and
Astronautics in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
After a LM-3B failed to launch the Intelsat 708 satellite on
February 15, 1996, the Chinese aerospace industry adopted strict
measures to minimize problems, improve the production process and
ensure the quality of its product, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
It established detailed regulations, including 72 articles for
production management, 28 articles for quality control and five
``go-no-go'' criteria, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"This is what's behind the 10 consecutive successes since
1996," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Underestimating the ability of Chinese rocket experts by some
Americans is "illogical and unreasonable," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. companies could suffer nearly one billion U.S. dollars in
losses if Washington banned them from continuing their contracts
with the CGWIC, Zhang said, adding that his company would turn to
European partners should such a ban be imposed.
</P>
<P>
Zhang disclosed that his company will launch a French-made
satellite next month.
</P>
<P>
The price tag of the CGWIC is competitive, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
