<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appliances From Big Chinese Manufacturers Are Good </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Gas ranges that are manufactured
by large or mid-sized Chinese companies are better than those from
small enterprises, according to a recent study by the State
Quality and Technology Supervision Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Of 37 brands of gas ranges examined in the cities of Beijing,
Tianjin and Shanghai, the provinces of Guangdong, Zhejiang,
Jiangsu, Shandong and Hunan, and the Guangxi Autonomous Region, 13
produced by large or mid-sized companies passed quality tests, but
only 66.7 percent of the products from 24 small enterprises passed.
</P>
<P>
Large and mid-sized companies pay more attention to product
quality and can provide better after-sale service, one Bureau
official says.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that the flame of smaller companies' ranges
burned improperly and had a high monoxide content and other
problems. Gas leakage around the valve was also a problem in some
products.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau has already published the results of the study and
asked the quality and technology supervision departments across
the country to stop sales of unqualified gas ranges and to crack
down on the production and selling of shoddy products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke062027 - Pakistani, Indian PMs to Meet at SAARC Summit in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif and his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee will have
an important meeting on fringes of the forthcoming SAARC summit in
Colombo, capital of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
During their bilateral meeting at Colombo, the two leaders "can
send their Foreign Secretaries back to the negotiating table,"
said a Foreign Office spokesman at a weekly briefing here Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The 10th summit meeting of the seven-nation South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) is scheduled to be
held in Colombo late July.
</P>
<P>
The Spokesman stressed the urgent need for talks and said there
could not be progress without addressing the core issue of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to play ball with India and have no
hesitation," he said.
</P>
<P>
But perhaps India has to realize that a policy of "hegemonism"
and the one which does not address the basic issue cannot promote
relations between the two sides in other areas, he noted.
</P>
<P>
As to the date of the Colombo summit, the spokesman said the
summit is newly proposed to take place from July 29 to 31 instead
of from July 20 to 22.
</P>
<P>
People are pinning high hopes on the Colombo meeting between
Sharif and Vajpayee to revitalize the foreign secretary-level
meeting which broke down in New Delhi last September.
</P>
<P>
Though both India and Pakistan have expressed willingness to
reopen the bilateral dialogue, the two countries are holding
different stances on the resumption of the foreign secretary level
talks.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan insists the talks should be resumed, with a parallel
international engagement, on the basis of the June 23 agreement
reached here by the two sides under which the core-issue of
Kashmir would be discussed.
</P>
<P>
But India, which refuses any third-party intervention, demands
the talks be started in light of proposals it made to Pakistan in
January this year, which Pakistan has rejected as "unrealistic and
unacceptable." 
</P>
