<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Detent Between Kuwaiti Parliament, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Crisis between Kuwaiti
government and legislature has been defused thanks to the
mediation by the emir, and "comprehensive contacts and frank
meetings" between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have pledged to begin close cooperation to serve the
country and the citizens, but observers here noted that the
reconciliation seems fragile.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the government and the National Assembly
soured earlier this month when the lawmakers led by Hussein
Al-Gallaf decided to grill Interior Minister Sheikh Mohammad
Al-Sabah, holding him responsible for widespread crimes and
corruption in various bodies of his ministry.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, came to the interior minister's
defense, praising him for good service and rejecting the
questioning.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers were also critical of laws proposed by the
government that would introduce taxes and fees for services that
have been heavily subsidized or offered free of charge for decades.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Sabah said the
parliament's rejection to the laws blocked the economic reforms
aimed at curbing budget deficit with the revenues from the
proposed charge hikes.
</P>
<P>
He then complained that his cabinet could no longer cooperate
with the 50-member legislature.
</P>
<P>
The confrontation raised broad speculation that either the
parliament or the government would be dissolved as a resolution.
</P>
<P>
Two previous Kuwaiti parliaments were dissolved in 1976 and
1986 respectively for severely criticizing the government.
</P>
<P>
To defuse the political crisis, Emir Sheik Jaber Al-Ahmed
Al-Sabah met with the cabinet on June 13, and received main
parliament leaders the following day.
</P>
<P>
The emir stressed "the need to stick to cooperation" between
the parliament and government, and the need to pool all efforts
for the good of the country. A reconciliation deal was reportedly
reached after his intervention.
</P>
<P>
On June 15, cabinet ministers headed by the prime minister met
with parliament members to discuss ways to promote bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
However, observers here were not fully confident about the
prospects of the cooperation, saying the parliament's opposition
to the government deficit reduction program was still pending.
</P>
<P>
The parliament has no sign to change its position, and hoped
the government achieve the deficit reduction goal through cutting
its spending and waste instead of raising charges.
</P>
<P>
It argued that raising charges will increase pressure on the
low-income citizens.
</P>
<P>
Besides, political observers said the legislature and the
government have many at adds.
</P>
<P>
Unsatisfied with government's inability in cracking down on
drug trafficking, the National Assembly decided last month to set
up a five-member panel to take charge of the implementation of the
drug laws.
</P>
<P>
But the government reacted strongly to the move, terming it an
intervention in the police work.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament has also complained about government's plans to
purchase out-of-date foreign weaponry and poor medical services.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here said there are still uncertain factors
ahead in Kuwait's political situation, which can rekindle a crisis
at any time in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
