<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protecting Chinese Women Against Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 20 (Xinhua) -- China is trying to give women
greater legal protection against social and domestic violence and
to help them guard their rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
Government departments have begun a serious crackdown on rape,
the abduction and selling of women, and on prostitution in the
past five years, according to Li Hui, a judge with the Supreme
People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Li told a seminar today that is a follow-up to the Fourth World
Conference on Women that cases of rape and the selling of women
account for a much smaller portion of the criminal cases than five
years ago, but instances of kidnapping of women and forced
prostitution are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
She said that China has set up 170 special courts at the
grass-roots level to handle cases of divorce, abandonment, and
domestic violence, and to teach women how to use legal means to
protect their rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
Domestic violence has caused bigger concern in the government
than before, but simply punishing the wrong-doers is not the final
solution to the problem, she explained, because it arises from a
number of factors like the unequal economic status of men and
women, sex discrimination, and the low education level of women,
and she suggested that there be measures to improve women's and
men's awareness of the law. The conception of family violence
should be more clearly defined by the law and judges who handle
cases of family violence should be given special training, she
said.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey by the All-China Women's
Federation (ACWF), 0.9 percent of Chinese women face the threat of
family violence, while 8.2 percent have been the victims of family
violence at least once.
</P>
<P>
The ACWF is planning organizations that can provide education
on family violence and the law, and can help victims of family
violence receive physical and mental health care, and provide them
with legal services, says Xu Weihua, an official with ACWF's Legal
Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
