<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said that his government is committed to fighting corruption and
that nobody is beyond the reach of the law when proved corrupt.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan president made the determination while meeting
with local and international human rights activists here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's Monitor daily quoted Museveni as saying:" There is
nobody who is untouchable when it comes to corruption, there is
nobody whom one can say that he is so politically strong that we
can't deal with him when proved corrupt."
</P>
<P>
He said, however, he faces technical problems to unearth and
eliminate corruption.
</P>
<P>
"For us we don't have any political problem in fighting
corruption but we lack investigative capacity. Our institutions
lack adequate auditors, accountants and prosecutors to give us
evidence about the corrupt," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He called on the human rights organizations to help detect and
investigate the corruption cases across the country.
</P>
<P>
A human rights activist said that rampant corruption in this
east African country has caused cynicism, scepticism and
discontent in the system and ultimately frustrated its work.
