<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Minister On Sino-U.S. Cultural Exchanges For 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The New York Philharmonic
Orchestra will present the last of its Asian concerts at Beijing's
Great Hall of the People on the eve of president Clinton's visit
here, barely a month after the Cleveland Orchestra performed for
an audience that included President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
In early July, the 600-year-old drama "Peony Pavilion",
referred to by some as China's Romeo and Juliet, will be performed
at New York's Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
These are a few of the cultural exchanges between China and the
U.S. that are developing in many ways, according to China's
Minister of Culture Sun Jiazheng, who told Xinhua that, during
President Jiang's visit to Washington last year, the two heads of
state agreed to establish a kind of constructive strategic
partnership for the 21st century between the two countries that
includes cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
During President Clinton's visit, a cultural contact plan for
the 1998-2001 period has been scheduled, the signing of which will
undoubtedly usher in a new era of cultural exchanges, Sun says.
</P>
<P>
However, he says, from the perspective of cultural exchanges
like films, radio, television, publishing and the performing arts,
China gets more than it exports, which is why the Chinese know
more about the U.S. than the Americans know about China. Even
people in remote villages receive prompt information on the U.S.,
but, the U.S. media seldom give objective coverage about China,
resulting in a lack of comprehensive and objective understanding
of China.
</P>
<P>
Of the 50 or 60 foreign films shown in Chinese cinemas each
year, some 15 to 20 come from the U.S. as do a large number of the
foreign television programs.
</P>
<P>
But, China will stick to its reforms and opening up and the
Chinese government welcomes the introduction of all culture that
is beneficial to the healthy development of the national economy
and culture, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
