<HEADLINE> Israel Rejects U.S. Flak of Greater Jerusalem Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Facing strong criticism by the
United States of its plan to expand Jerusalem, Israel quickly
defended itself by saying the plan would not change the status of
the West Bank, Israel Radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media advisor to Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, was trying to fend off the U.S. censure. He was quoted
by the radio as saying Israel has no intention to annex
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin Friday dismissed
the Israeli plan, endorsed by Netanyahu Thursday with the aim of
strengthening the Jewish state's hold on the holy city in dispute,
as "extremely provocative."
</P>
<P>
He said it is "hard to understand" why Israel has taken such a
step at "a sensitive time" in the negotiations with Palestinians
over the second pullback from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had conveyed
her displeasure to Netanyahu in a telephone call. She had also
called to a dozen leaders of American Jewish communities to
express her annoyance over the plan and, according to one of the
leaders, had asked the Israeli cabinet to reconsider it.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu formally received the controversial plan Thursday
from a committee which comprises of directors-general of the
Prime Minister's Office, the interior minister, and members from
the Jerusalem Municipality and Jerusalem Development. At the
ceremony, he reiterated that Jerusalem is the sovereign capital of
Israel, and that Israel, and Israel alone, has the sovereignty
over the city.
</P>
<P>
According to the 12-point plan, a ring road around east
Jerusalem will be constructed, a tunnel will be built under Mount
Scopus to connect with Maaleh Adumim, one of the biggest Jewish
settlements in east Jerusalem. Meanwhile, measures will be taken
to boost investment in the city and attract more Jews there.
</P>
<P>
The plan also caused resentment among residents in communities
west of the Jerusalem, who have objected to the annexing of their
land for expanding Jerusalem westward.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu described the plan as "a basic change in Jerusalem's
status which will be remembered as a turning point."
</P>
<P>
"The first thing we are doing is to link Greater Jerusalem," he
said, referring to the planned tunnel and ring road. "The second
thing is strengthing the Jewish majority in Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
The status of Jerusalem is one of the most sensitive and
contentious issues in Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. For its
emotional and potentially explosive significance, negotiations
over Jerusalem have been postponed to the permanent status talks.
</P>
<P>
Before the talks take place, concerned sides are required to
refrain from taking unilateral actions to change the status,
demographic composition or character of the city.
</P>
<P>
The expansion plan came at a time when tensions were flaring up
between Israel and the Palestinians over increasing Jewish
settlement activities in the Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have also complained that Israel has intensified
its work of demolishing Palestinian houses, which the Israeli side
said were built without permits.
</P>
<P>
The plan, to be funded under the 1999 Israeli state budget,
will be presented to the cabinet Sunday for discussion.
"Jerusalem will stand at the top of our priorities in the budget
framework," Finance Minister Ya'acov Neeman has been quoted by the
Israeli media as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
