<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gauteng Province Remains S. Africa's Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 20 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Gauteng province,
where Johannesburg and Pretoria are located, remains the crime capital
of South Africa, heading the other provinces in almost all serious
crimes, The Citizen daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than half of all motor vehicle and motorcycle
thefts in South Africa, as well as more than half of all car
hijackings, occurred in Gauteng Province, the richest province in
the country, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi as
saying Friday that only 14 percent of the motor hijackings or
thefts were solved.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi was answering questions in parliament by opposition
Democratic Party member, Douglas Gibson.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Gauteng recorded 5,645 cases of murder last year,
as compared with 6,200 in Kwazulu-Natal and 4,219 in Eastern Cape.
</P>
<P>
However, in culpable homicide, Gauteng led with 3,071 cases, over
Kwazulu-Natal with 2,611 and Eastern Cape with 1,606.
</P>
<P>
This means that 23 percent of all criminal deaths in 1997 took
place in Gauteng.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 20.5 percent of assaults, 24 percent of rapes or attempted
rapes, and 37 percent of robberies in the country occurred in Gauteng
last year.
</P>
<P>
Central Johannesburg and Johannesburg's red-light district of
Hillbrow continue to head the crime figures for the 20 police stations
in the central Gauteng area, according to Mufamadi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
