<HEADLINE> APEC Senior Officials Meeting Ends in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUCHING (Malaysia), June 20 (Xinhua) -- The three-day second
Senior Officials Meeting (SOM II) of the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) ended here Saturday without agreement on Early
Voluntary Sectoral Liberalization (EVSL).
</P>
<P>
SOM II failed to reach agreement mainly due to some different
views on the flexibility of the EVSL, Executive Director of the
APEC Secretariat and Singapore Ambassador Noor Adlan said while
briefing reporters on the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The flexibility is a decision point that will be left to APEC
ministers responsible for trade to take decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the EVSL as "the most important agenda and the key
issue" at the SOM meeting which he said will present a status
report on the issue to the APEC trade ministers who will meet here
on June 22 and 23.
</P>
<P>
Adlan did not say which APEC members are demanding flexibility.
</P>
<P>
He said Chile and Mexico are out of the EVSL as they are on
another track for trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the SOM meeting agreed on other agendas such
as Economic and Technical Cooperation (ECOTECH) as well as on
issues relating to the APEC management process including
business/private sector participation process.
</P>
<P>
It also studied a wide range of issues on electronic commerce
and reached agreement on that.
</P>
<P>
The SOM meeting was attended by all the APEC members --
Australia; Brunei; Canada; China; Chinese Taipei; Chile; Hong
Kong, China; Indonesia; Japan; South Korea; Malaysia; Mexico; New
Zealand; Papua New Guinea; the Philippines; Singapore; Thailand
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
APEC members-to-be -- Peru, Russia and Vietnam -- also attended
the SOM meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
