Botha's trial for snubbing the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission subpoena was postponed Monday until August 17. A
verdict is expected on the following day.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, Botha faces a sentence of up to two years or a
fine of up to 20,000 Rand (about 3,700 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Botha was put on trial after ignoring repeatedly a subpoena of
the TRC for hearings on the now defunct State Security Council,
which he chaired in the 1980s. The TRC was investigating alleged
gross human rights violations of the council.  
