<HEADLINE> UNHCR Stresses Refugee Problem in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High Commission for
Refugees (UNHCR) has reiterated the need for African leaders to seek
solutions to the refugee problem in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The organization urged African leaders to replace the language of
confrontation with that of consultation in resolving their differences
to stem the scourge of refugee problems currently plaguing Africa.
</P>
<P>
This is the highlight of a statement issued by UNHCR Representative
in Nigeria, Guebre-Christos, on the occasion of African Refugees' Day
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The statement lamented the spate of refugee crises in Africa,
saying that instead of abating, it is increasing at an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, 18 million people have been
uprooted from their homes worldwide. Of the figure, six million can be
found in Africa. One out of every 35 Africans is either a refugee or
displaced person.
</P>
<P>
Citing the need to hold peaceful talks in resolving issues, the
UNHCR official said, most refugee problems would have either been
prevented or solved, if leaders and aggrieved parties took pains
to mobilize all peaceful resources to resolve the crises.
</P>
<P>
Although efforts have been made to resettle and take care of
refugees in Rwanda, Tanzania, Algeria, Mali and Liberia, UNHCR is
beset with a myriad of problems hindering its operation, the
Guebre-Christos said.
</P>
<P>
"A stable peace in the region will in part depend on their
(refugees) successful return and reintegration," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
