<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Papers Urge "Practical" US Moves on Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Two Iranian dailies representing
both the moderate and conservative factions all called on the
U.S. to take "practical actions" instead of "mere words" to pull
down the "wall of mistrust" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In their editorials Saturday, the two papers said U.S.
officials must know the wall of mistrust cannot come down with
mere words, it needs genuine practical moves, such as lifting
sanctions against Tehran and releasing the Iranian assests frozen
in American banks for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
The calls came in reaction to ground-breaking statements made
by President Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, saying that Washington wanted genuine reconciliation
with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The pro-moderate Iran News noted the recent Washington
statements "are considerably different from the previous ones,"
but added that as long as the U.S. officials stress on words, not
actions, it is unlikely to solve the outstanding problems between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It also blamed Clinton for repeating the allegations such as
Iran's support for terrorism, efforts to seek weapons of mass
destruction and opposition to the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the conservative daily Tehran Times stressed the
importance of U.S. actions in warming bonds with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The paper blamed the U.S. administration for submitting to the
Israeli lobby in the congress.
</P>
<P>
It said that both Washington and Tehran should "be careful as
pro-Zionist Republicans will do their best to poison the political
climate which now exists between Islamic Iran and world's oldest
democracy, the United States."
</P>
<P>
It also stressed that Tehran-Washington relations should be
based on mutual respect and non-interference in each other's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Kicking the ball back to the U.S. court, Iran's Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi has reiterated Tehran's consistent stand
that the U.S. must change its "hostile policies" towards Iran
before a possible normalization in ties.
</P>
<P>
But according to Iran's constitution, Iranian supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei is the ultimate authority to make final
decision on Tehran's relations with Washington, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
