<HEADLINE> ASEAN, FOC Happy With Poll Preparation in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) troika and the Friends of Cambodia (FOC) are
satisfied with the preparations for the Cambodian elections
scheduled for July 26, the Troika's top diplomats said here
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the satisfaction at a press conference right
after a meeting between the ASEAN Troika, consisting of Thailand,
Indonesia and the Philippines, and the Friends of Cambodia, namely
Australia, Canada, the United States, the European Union and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon read a troika
statement, saying the three countries support the important role
of Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk in helping restore the
country's political stability, especially his call Wednesday on
the Cambodian people to exercise their right to vote without fear.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 90 percent of the eligible voters have registered
to take part in polling, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The troika statement also underscored the value of
international observation of the electoral process under U.N.
coordination to achieve free, fair and credible elections, saying
the ASEAN will send its own observers.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Indonesia and Thailand plan to send eight
observers while the Philippines is expected to send between 10 and
12.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said his
country had appealed to the participants of the meeting to
sympathize with "the burden Thailand is now shouldering."
</P>
<P>
He referred to the 55,000 displaced Cambodians on Thai soil,
particularly on the eastern border.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand is very hopeful that (these people) would be able to
return as soon as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a separate communique, the Friends of Cambodia urged the
Cambodian government to ensure that all political parties be given
equitable access to the media.
</P>
<P>
They also "strongly encouraged" the Cambodian government to
take measures to ensure the integrity and secrecy of voting and
the ballot count, as well as the participation and safety of
national and international observers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
