<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Hike Hampers S. African Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Standard Bank, the
second biggest bank in South Africa, announced Friday night that
it had lifted its interest rate by one percentage point, from
20.25 percent to 21.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made following Absa, the biggest
commercial bank in the country, raised its lending rate and
mortagage lending rates by two percentage points 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
By June 15, the First National Bank and two other major banks
in South Africa had followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Standard Bank's move came a few hours after South Africa's
Reserve Bank allowed its lending rates to the banks to climb to
the highest level in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
The key repurchase or "repo" rate shot up nearly four
percentage points to nearly 20.4 percent as the Reserve Bank
tried to soothe turbulent financial market where the Rand, South
Africa's national currency, had slid to a new low of 5.52 to the
U.S. dollar. At the start of this week, one U.S.Dollar equals
about 5.30 Rand.
</P>
<P>
The Rand closed Friday night at 5.47 to the Dollar and 9.16 to
the British Pound. It has lost more than 13 percent against the
Dollar this year, as investors, nervous about fall-out from
Asia's economic crisis, have fled emerging markets, including
South Africa, to take refuge in the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Unless stabilty returns to financial markets quickly, other
banks will be forced to increase their interest rates, economists
said, predicting that the higher cost of borrowing will be a
severe set-back for chances of South African economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Economists here are reportedly revising their growth hopes for
the full year down to a range between one percent and 1.5
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
