<HEADLINE> School Children in Pursuit of Brandname Worry Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 20 (Xinhua) -- A signed article carried by
today's Guangming Daily voices anxiety over the growing trend
in brandname-conscious small children in China.
</P>
<P>
By chance, the author of the article met a three-grade school
girl who could recite a dozen Chinese and foreign brandname
products she care for so much or happen to know.
</P>
<P>
This led the author to conduct an investigative survey in the
Hanzhong St. Primary School in Nanjing, east China's Jiangsu
Province. In one class, all the pupils were fond of writing down a
dozen brandnames, whereas in another class, no pupil surveyed said
"no" to the querry "who so far has not used a brandname commodity."
</P>
<P>
This outcome of the survey surprised not only the author, the
teachers, but some department store salespeople who found to know
far fewer brandnames themselves than primary school children,
according to the article.
</P>
<P>
Fu Hong, a children psychologist of the Nanjing Normal
University was quoted as saying that the phenomenon is mainly
attributed to the influence of advertising.
</P>
<P>
The rapid increase in ads of children's goods, he noted, can
easily arouse the children's curiosity and exert a subtle,
negative impact on their consuming behavior.
</P>
<P>
The parents who tend to spoil their only child and who
can hardly resist the temptation of the brand name products
themselves pose another problem.
</P>
<P>
Children's strong desire for brandnames is worrisome since it
engenders the sense of vanity and detrimentally affects their
psychology, Fu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
