<HEADLINE> First Egyptian Oil Company Offered for Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Egypt opened up its oil sector to
private investors for the first time Friday, offering them a 35
percent stake in the capital of a newly-established crude refining
and processing firm, the Egyptian Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35.7 million shares of Misr Petroleum Processing
Company were offered for Egyptian and foreign investors, with each
share at 10 pounds (about 2.9 U.S. dollars), the paper said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first public offering in oil sector in Egypt,
according to the paper. It marks a U-turn in Egypt's privatization
policy.
</P>
<P>
Oil Minister Hamdi Al-Banbi had insisted that the state would
not privatize Egypt's oil refineries and firms because they
perform a "strategic, national role."
</P>
<P>
Since it launched privatization program in earnest in 1996,
Egyptian government has sold majority stakes in scores of firms,
forgone its interest in mobile telephone network and offered
infrastructure and utilities projects to private investors.
</P>
<P>
Egypt sells 10 companies every three months and 105 out of 314
state-owned companies have been offered for sale under the
privatization program, according to the Ministry of the Public
Enterprise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
