<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Budget Deficit Falls Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The budget deficit of the Thai
government fell sharply to about 15 billion baht (375 million U.S.
dollars) in the first eight months of the 1998 fiscal year, which
started last October, a Finance Ministry statement said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit in the same period last year was 54 billion
baht (1.36 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, state revenue from October 1 to May
31 totaled 491 billion baht (12.3 billion dollars) while
expenditure stood at 506 billion baht (12.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The country had a cash deficit of 18.7 billion baht (467.5
million dollars) when a 3.5 billion-baht (88.5 million dollars)
deficit of non-budgetary revenue was included, compared with 41.5
billion baht (1.04 billion dollars) in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from tax revenue for the first eight months of the
fiscal year totaled 547 billion baht (13.7 billion dollars), down
10.2 percent from the same period of last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The government also earned 32.8 billion baht (819 million
dollars) from contributions by state enterprises during the
period, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
