<HEADLINE> Greene Ties World 100m Record in 9.84 Seconds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Maurice Greence, world champion
last year who said he would beat world 100-meter record this year,
equalled the record Friday night at the USA track and field
championships in New Orleans of the United States, according to a
press report today.
</P>
<P>
Greene's mark tied the world best set by Canada's Donovan
Bailey in the 1996 Olympics. However, a tail-wind of 3.3 meters
per second negated the mark, which came in a quarter-final heat.
</P>
<P>
Greene ran even faster on May 31 at Eugene, clocking 9.79 with
a strong wind behind him at the Prefontaine Classic meet.
</P>
<P>
Three other runners - Obadele Thompson, Carl Lewis and Andre
Cason, all Americans, have run under 9.84, all wind-aided.
</P>
<P>
Greene, 23, has a personal best 9.86. He said:"It was terrible,
technically terrible. My mind wasn't in it. I was not focused. My
mind was wandering around."
</P>
<P>
Marion Jones, the women's 100-meter world champion, also ran a
fast time in her quarter-final heat, clocking a wind-aided
10.75. The wind on Jones' race was 4.1 meters per second. 
</P>
</TEXT>
