<HEADLINE> Xi'an College Students, Teachers Optimistic on Sino-US Ties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Students and faculty members of the
institutions of higher learning in this capital of northwestern
Shaanxi province, either Chinese or foreign, appreciate President
Bill Clinton's imminent China trip, and expressed their optimism
on the prospects of Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an will be the first stop of Clinton's visit, the first
state visit by a US president to China in a decade.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yu, a graduate student in the Business School of Xi'an
Jiaotong University, said President Jiang Zemin's visit to the US
last fall opened up a new page for Sino-Us bilateral ties, and he
expected Clinton's trip to play a positive role in developing
friendship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Qu Miao, an undergraduate of the university's Department of
Economy, spoke highly of President Clinton's decisions to visit
China and to extend China's MFN status as "wise".
</P>
<P>
Adam Hickey, an exchange student from Illinois, said that
President Bill Clinton's visit will help increase mutual
understandings and the in-depth development of economic and
cultural exchanges between the two countries with considerable
impact to be exerted on the international arena.
</P>
<P>
Some political organizations in the United States, in an
attempt to win more votes or proceeding from their political
needs, may give some remarks unfavourable to China, which does
not represent the wishes of the American people, said Betty
F. Coggin, an English teacher at Xi'an Foreign Languages Institute.
</P>
<P>
However, she held that the US president's visit to China will
play a positive role in removing barriers between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin's successful trip to the US last fall and
President Bill Clinton's coming visit to China will be of great
importance for the two nations to build a strategic partnership
for the 21st century, said Dr. Huang Minxing of Northwest
University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0143 </DOCNO>
