<HEADLINE> Hoodle Urges to Bring Back Common Sense Back to Refereeing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- England manager Glenn Hoddle urged a
return of "common sense" back into the World Cup refereeing after a
wave of red and yellow cards dominated the play in recent games.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle said:"I think in the first matches the (refereeing)
balance was right. There might have been a couple of isolated fouls
which could have resulted in red cards but all in all it wasn't too bad."
</P>
<P>
"We had the first five days of the tournament to look at what was
going to happen and how they were going to interpret the laws. But it
is almost as if we're starting all over again." said Hoddle.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously it is a worry. As long as it's the tackle from
behind that's punished, that's fine. But it's got to be sensible
and have a balance about it." Hoddle added. 
