<HEADLINE> Deputy Finance Ministers Meet to Seek Currency Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Deputies of the finance ministers
and central bank governors from eighteen countries and regions are
holding an emergency meeting in Tokyo on Saturday to seek ways to
stabilize international currencies.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting is expected to issue a statement showing
the participants' willingness to cooperate in stabilizing global
currency markets.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the meeting will reconfirm the necessity to
rectify the excessive depreciation of the Japanese yen against the
U.S. dollar, following the recent joint intervention by Japan and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The deputies will also urge Japan to make further efforts,
including disposing of bad loans and reforming its tax system to
turn its economy around, so that it can help other Asian economies
recover by absorbing more imports from the region.
</P>
<P>
They are also to discuss the potential effects of China's
possible devaluation of its currency on fears that the country's
exports will lose competitive edge in the wake of the yen's
decline against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is attended by delegates from Australia, Brunei,
China, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Malaysia, New Zealand, the
Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, Thailand and the G-7 nations,
together with representatives from the International Monetary
Fund, the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
G-7 groups Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and
the U.S. 
</P>
