<HEADLINE> Kenya Bank Employees to Act over Loans Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan bankers are set for
another showdown with the government over the taxation of
benefits arising from employer-subsidized low interest rate
loans.
</P>
<P>
All Banks Shopstewards Committee (ABSC) has rejected the
proposed financial bill on taxation of the low interest rate on
staff loan facilities, the East African Standard newspaper
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
ABSC Chairman Jacob Opiyo threatened Friday to call
unionizable banking employees out on strike next week to protest
the move, saying the committee was facing mounting pressure from
the bank workers who are becoming too wild and uncontrollable.
</P>
<P>
He said that a meeting of all bank workers which will decide
on the next course of action have been called for Thursday next
week in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is against the Income Tax Act as borrowed money
is not an allowance received in respect of employment or services
rendered or gains or profits derived from employment.
</P>
<P>
"A loan is an expense which is repaid back every month plus
interest and therefore should not be treated as an employment
benefit," said Opiyo.
</P>
<P>
He said the taxation element at a prescribed rate on interest
at 15 percent will eat away all the net pay of bank workers.
</P>
<P>
Opiyo vowed that bankers would not sit down while the benefits
they have enjoyed for many years are taken away overnight.
</P>
<P>
"Bank workers can never work for negative salaries and if we
go on strike this time round we will never resume work until the
minister for finance scraps the entire tax on staff loan
facilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bank employees' strike earlier this year over the same dispute
ended with a retreat by the government which afterwards suspended
measures trying to collect this kind of taxation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
