<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Capital Most Visited City in China  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 20 (Xinhua) -- When Shenzhen and Shanghai, two
economic powerhouses along China's coastlines, represent China's
dramatic changes during the past two decades of reform and
opening-up, the ancient capitals of Beijing and Xi'an remain the
ideal sites for visitors to get a glimpse of the country's
splendid history.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an, currently the capital of northwest China's Shaanxi
province and the first stop of US President Bill Clinton's
imminent state visit to China, has become one of the most popular
destinations in China for international tourists with its rich and
invaluable collection of cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an played the host to some 485,000 visitors from overseas
last year, earning 201 million US dollars in foreign exchanges, up
by 6.9 percent and 11.6 percent over 1996. Foreign visitors
accounted for 83 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Japanese tourists, totaling 143,000 last year, formed the
the bulk of foreign tourists, followed by the United States,
Britain, Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
Terra-cotta warriors unearthed near the Mausoleum of Qin Shi
Huang, or the first emperor of the Qin Dynasty (221-206 BC), is
the hottest and most famous tourist attraction in Xi'an. Since it
was first opened to visitors in October 1979, the Terra-cotta
Warriors Museum has received more than four million overseas
visitors, including foreign heads of states like former US
President Ronald Reagon, British Queen Elizabeth the Second,
former French President Francois Mitterrand, German Chancellor
Helmet Kohl and former Japanese prime ministers Noboru Takeshita
and Masayoshi Ohira and many other prestigious world statesmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Capital Most Visited City in China-2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Among some other renowned sites of historic interest are the
Ruins of the Banpo village, a site of the new stone period more
than 6,000 years ago, which has been turned into China's first
museum of relics from the primitive society; the Sha'anxi Museum;
the Big Wild Goose Pagoda and the Small Wild Goose Pagoda, both
built in Tang Dynasty (618-907); as well as the Forest of Steles
-- China's largest stone library.
</P>
<P>
A tourism network, radiating from the ancient capital of Xi'an,
has also taken shaped, with adjacent dotted historic sites such as
Huaqingchi -- an imperial park of the Tang Dynasty; Qianling --
the mausoleum of Empress Wu Zetian of Tang Dynasty (618-907), the
only woman in the Chinese history who proclaimed herself as the
sovereign; the Famen Temple which collects relics of Sakyamuni's
finger bone and a large amount of priceless imperial valuables of
Tang Dynasty; and the Mausoleum of Huangdi, the legendary founder
of the Chinese nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Gold Mine Opens in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- A five million U.S. Dollar
alluvial gold mine, to be jointly developed by Zimbabwean and
Russian firms jointly, was commissioned Friday near Penhalonga of
east Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The mine, a joint venture between the Development Trust of
Zimbabwe (DTZ) and a Russian company, Ozgeo, is the first of its
kind in Zimbabwe to engage in large-scale extraction and
processing of alluvial gold.
</P>
<P>
The venture came at a time when gold prices on the
international market have plummeted, throwing most gold mining
companies into viability crises.
</P>
<P>
The Dtz-Ozgeo joint venture, situated in the Mutare River
Valley, was awarded a special permit by the government
authorizing it to carry out mining activities within 500 meters
from the center to both sides of the river, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the mine's official opening ceremony, Zimbabwe's
Mines, Environment and Tourism Minister Simon Moyo expressed
satisfaction that the project will not adversely affect the
environment.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that environmental impact assessment studies
were not conducted, he said,the techniques of alluvial gold
extraction and washing are highly sophisticated and
environmentally friendly.
</P>
<P>
"Special attention has been placed on the protection of the
environment without any losses in efficiency. No toxic chemicals
are used in the entire mining process," Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
"Of great relief is that a closed water reticulation system is
used and no contaminated water enters Mutare river system," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Moyo noted that the venture's project proposals indicated that
at the end of the mining operations all land will be restored to
its original state through backfilling.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
