<HEADLINE> Dar es Salaam Bothered by Vandalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Vandalism of public
utilities has become a headache of the Dar es Salaam City
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Senior Public Relations Officer of the commission, Angelus
Machege, has said that the street lamps and their starters,
manhole covers, sign posts and bridges railings have become the
target of attack.
</P>
<P>
Damages of the properties have caused the capital city a loss
of 32 million Tanzanian Shillings (about 48,000 US dollars), the
Daily Mail Saturday quoted Machege as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official told the paper Friday that with street lights
vandalized, many areas are left in darkness at night, providing
shelter for bandits, he said. "With muggers around our safety is
threatened."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that missing manhole covers and bridges
safety railings could cause accidents. The items were either sold
or used for private purposes.
</P>
<P>
The official has called on governments of various districts to
take greater care of the public facilities.  
</P>
