<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Gains in depressed Money Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Shilling is expected
to remain on the offensive next week after being strengthened
marginally against the U.S. Dollar in Friday's trading in a
depressed money market, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Corporate buyers have showed little interest in picking up
dollars despite the attractive offers, they were quoted by
Saturday's Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dealers quoted the Shilling at around 59.55 Shillings buying
and 59.75 Shillings selling to the Dollar but closed at 59.80
Shillings buying and 60 Shillings selling Friday.
</P>
<P>
Importers' demand for Dollars remains low, while export
inflows of hard currency from tea and coffee sales are putting
upward pressure on the Shilling, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
They said the market was sluggish reflecting the generally low
economic activity as well as the usual end-of-week slowdown in
trading.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) quoted the Shilling at a
commercial mean opening rate of 59.71 Shillings to the Dollar and
99.72 Shillings to the Sterling Pound compared to 59.85 Shillings
and 99.73 Shillings Thursday respectively.
</P>
<P>
The effects of high world tea prices, favorable weather
conditions and a bumper crop started to show this week with
companies in the tea sector starting to report a tremendous rise
in profits.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Treasury bill market said the Thursday
auction recorded an average yield of 25.4 percent on the 91-day
tenor.
</P>
<P>
CBK was able to sell 91-day bills worth 5.38 billion Shillings
and 182-day bills worth 1.75 billion Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks have also started lowering base lending rates
following a reduction of the cash ratio. The market is also
watching to see where the government will turn to for money after
exhausting its limit with CBK.
</P>
<P>
At the Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE), trading slackened during
the week with turnover dropping to 82 million Shillings from 157
million Shillings last week.
</P>
<P>
The number of shares also fell to 1.3 million from 2.6 million
last week. The NSE 20 share index ended the week down 29.68
points to close at 2960.34.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector dominated the trading moving 548.000
Shares which accounted for 39.33 percent of the week's volume.
</P>
<P>
Barclays Bank moved 127,000 shares at between 99 Shillings and
