<HEADLINE> Dhaka's Exports Grow by 16.75 percent in 10 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's exports grew by 16.75
percent and earned 188.46 billion taka (about 4.1 billion U.S.
dollars), about 10 million dollars less than the target, during
the first 10 months of the July 1997-June 1998 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Major export items like knitwear and hosiery products, raw jute
and jute goods, frozen foods and leather fell short of target in
the period, the English newspaper The Daily Star said Saturday
quoting the latest statistics of the Export Promotion Bureau
(EPB).
</P>
<P>
The overall export target would be hopefully achieved at the
end of the current fiscal year, the report quoted EPB Chairman
Fraisal Ahmed Chowdhury as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's 36.93 percent of export revenue came from the U.S
market which imported 1.541 billion dollars worth of Bangladesh's
products during the period.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. buyers imported ready-made garments from the country
worth about 1.155 billion dollars, frozen shrimp worth 124 million
dollars, and knitwear valued at 169 million dollars in the period.
 
</P>
