<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Set Terms for Debt Talks with Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Romania will send a letter to
the Swedish Government to present its terms for resuming talks on
a 69-year-old debt which Romania owes Sweden, the local daily
National Monitor reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The debt, a 27 million-U.S.-dollar loan from Sweden in 1929,
has snowballed to about 3.5 billion U.S. dollars, according to an
estimate by the International audit firm Arthur Aandersen Agency.
</P>
<P>
This week, a commission for analyzing Sweden's debt claim
presented the cabinet with a report, setting preconditions for the
debt talks.
</P>
<P>
The report recommended that the Swedish side follow the
precedent of previous debt settlements between Romania and 14
other nations and that the negotiations should be at a government-
to-government level rather than government-to-company level.
</P>
<P>
If these conditions are met, the Ministers of Foreign Affairs,
Justice, Finance, and Industry and Trade will designate
international law experts to be included in the new negotiating
commission, the report proposed.
</P>
<P>
Swedish authorities said the loan was due in 1959, but they
had not received the money back.
</P>
<P>
In 1989 Sweden requested the repayment of the debt and
authorized the AB Electro Invest firm to negotiate with the
Romanian government. No agreement was reached as the two sides
differed regarding the amount of the debt.
</P>
<P>
After the 1996 elections, the Ciorbea-led government, prompted
by repeated calls from Poul Thomsen, an International Monetary
Fund negotiator and a Swedish national, showed willingness to
resume negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Romanian Finance Minister Mircea Ciumara, who was
leading the Romanian team in the negotiations, reportedly agreed
to pay Sweden 800 million U.S. dollars for the debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
