<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Disburse Credit to Help Rural Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is to provide 800 million
taka (17.4 million U.S. dollars) as micro-credit for the rural
poor during the 1998-98 financial year beginning July 1, a press
release reaching here Saturday said.
</P>
<P>
Since the project, the "Rural Bittaheen Program" of the Rural
Development Board, was started several years ago, some 16,900
Bittaheen Samabaya Samity (association of the rural destitute)
with about 474,800 members have been formed. And the members have
accumulated an amount of 375.3 million taka (about 8.16 million
dollars) as their own capital through weekly savings and purchase
of shares.
</P>
<P>
About 352,500 members of destitute families throughout the
country have received a total of 4.068 billion taka (about 88.42
million dollars) in micro-credit for income-generating activities
like pisciculture, mat making, tailoring, nurseries, small
trading, rickshaw pulling, pottery and handicraft.
</P>
<P>
Apart form the credit, about 275,000 members so far have also
received training in social development, skill development and
cooperative management.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of about 127 million Bangladeshis live in poverty
and the project is part of the government's effort to reduce
poverty in the South Asian country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
