<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanctions to Hit India's Economy Long-term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Although the Indian government
said that the Untied States sanctions against India are
"counter-productive" and just a "minor road block" in furthering
Indo-U.S. trade relations, they are bound to have an adverse
impact on the country's economy in the long run, economic experts
said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Indications are that the country's infrastructure projects
would be the hardest hit with both multi-lateral and bilateral
funds drying up, especially fund from the World Bank, the Asian
Development Bank and OECF of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank board meeting on May 27 - to consider four major
loans for India's power, irrigation and roads sectors - was
postponed. This has turned the prospects of the 1.2 billion U.S.
dollars inflow very bleak, they said.
</P>
<P>
Since all fresh loans and concessional funds have been stopped
forthwith, the Power Finance Corporation's proposal for 500
million U.S. dollars each from the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank is also in limbo. Several such loan proposals,
especially in the power sector, are bound to take a beating with
the G-8 endorsing the United States move to block multi-lateral
fund flow to India. The proposed one billion dollars loan to
India's Power Grid Corporation would also not materialize.
</P>
<P>
The drying up of funds from bilateral and multi-lateral
agencies is expected to result in a repayment problem for India,
since a large chunk of debt funds are utilized to make interest
related payments.
</P>
<P>
The denial of the U.S. exim bank guarantees is expected to make
funds costlier in the international debt market for Indian
corporations, especially pursuing infrastructure projects, they
further said.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office (PMO) has been reportedly turned
into a hub of activity of drafting a blueprint to tackle the
sanctions. The finance minister convened a meeting of secretaries
heading economic ministries. The sanctions also came up for
discussion at the meeting of the Parliamentary Standing Committee
on Finance, where Opposition members demanded an action plan to
tackle the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Declines in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total trade at
current prices declined by 6.1 percent in May 1998 over the same
month of 1997 on a three-month moving average basis, the country's
Trade Development Board (TDB) said in a press release Saturday.
</P>
<P>
By breakdown, imports shrank by 12 percent and exports
increased by 0.1 percent, with 1.1 percent increase in non-oil
domestic exports and 3.0 percent rise in non-oil re-exports and a
further 16.4 percent plunge in oil domestic exports, the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
Total trade volume fell by 1.8 billion Singapore dollars (1.05
billion U.S. dollars) to 27.31 billion Singapore dollars (1.59
billion U.S. dollars) compared with April this year.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic exports increased by 1.1 percent to 7.1
billion Singapore dollars (4.13 billion U.S. dollars). Growth in
non-oil domestic exports to the U.S. and Europe slowed down to 7.8
percent and 10.1 percent over May 1997, after recording growths of
17.4 percent and 14.1 percent in April 1998. Non-oil domestic
exports to the regional economies as well as other major Asian
economies in May dropped with those to Malaysia, South Korea and
Japan down by 16.7 percent, 30.8 percent and 12.4 per cent
respectively over the same period last year, according to TDB.
</P>
<P>
Domestic exports of oil remained weak in May 1998, falling by
16.4 percent over May 1997.
</P>
<P>
Compared with May 1997, growth in non-oil re-exports also
moderated, increasing by only 3 percent to a level of 6.2 billion
Singapore dollars (3.6 billion U.S. dollars) in May 1998 while
non-oil imports shrank by 10 percent to reach a level of 11.9
billion Singapore dollars (6.92 U.S. dollars) the same month.
</P>
<P>
Declines were recorded in imports of integrated circuits,
PCBAs, blank computer tapes and discs, capacitors, parts of CTVs,
radios and VCRs and parts of aircraft, TDB said.
</P>
<P>
TDB attributed the weak performance to the oversupply of key
electronic products in the global market as well as the regional
economic crisis which has affected Singapore's exports to the
affected economies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
