<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh's Pharmaceutical Industry Makes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has made remarkable
achievements in developing its own pharmaceutical industry since
the early 1980s, which can now meet 95 percent of the country's
demand for medicine.
</P>
<P>
The achievements are the result of the Drug (Control) Ordinance
the government promulgated in 1982 to expedite the sector's
development, to remove "harmful, useless and unnecessary"
medicines from the market and to ensure the supply of essential
drugs to ordinary people at affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
In 1981, there were 166 licensed pharmaceutical companies in
the country, but the domestic medicine market was dominated by
eight multinational companies producing about 75 percent of the
products.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five medium-sized national companies at that time
produced only 15 percent of the products, with the remaining 10
percent manufactured by 133 small national companies. And these
local pharmaceutical companies were mainly engaged in formulation
with imported raw materials, spending about 600 million taka (13
million U.S. dollars) annually in foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
With 166 local pharmaceutical production units, the country
still had to spend nearly 300 million taka (6.5 million dollars) a
year importing finished medicines.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Drug Ordinance 1982 has shown positive
impact on the country's pharmaceutical sector, with dependence on
imported drugs significantly lowered and foreign currency funds
utilized for importing only medicines not produced in the country.
</P>
<P>
The value of locally-produced medicines rose from 1.1 billion
taka (23.9 million dollars) in 1981 to 13.5 billion taka (294
million dollars) in 1997, while the share of essential drugs
increased significantly from 30 percent in 1981 to 64 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
At present, 95 percent of the domestic demand for medicines has
been met by local production, and government- and local
people-owned  pharmaceutical companies increased their share of
medicine output from 25 percent in 1981 to 65 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Now there are 207 licensed drug manufacturing units in the
country producing about 5,600 brands of medicines, and there are
altogether 1,338 wholesale drug licensed units and 35,000 retail
drug license holders in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Another remarkable progress the local pharmaceutical industry
has made since 1982 is the increase in the local production of
basic chemicals as well as their exports worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The growth in the pharmaceutical industry has also helped the
development of auxiliary industries making products such as glass
bottles, plastic containers, aluminum collapsible tubes, infusion
sets, disposable syringes and corrugated cartons. Some of these
products, after meeting the country's requirements, are also
exported to other countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Bangladesh exported medicines worth of 220 million
taka (4.35 million dollars) to Vietnam, Singapore, Russia,
Pakistan, Thailand, the United States, as well as Central Asian
and African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
