<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Urged to Lead in Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government should play a
leading role in the country's economic recovery by spurring
domestic demand and pushing forward with corporate debt
restructuring, the Bangkok Post Saturday quoted a World Bank
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
When addressing a business meeting Friday, Jayasankar
Shivakumar, country director for the World Bank, said the
government needed to adopt fiscal measures to inject liquidity
into the market to boost domestic demand and prevent the economy
sliding into a depression.
</P>
<P>
"During the past 10 years, the private sector led the economy
while the government was passive. But during this situation, the
government has to lead, orchestrate the work and maintain good
teamwork," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Shivakumar praised the achievements of the Chuan Leekpai
government, saying it had begun to win back confidence of the
international business community with its restructuring of the
economic and financial sector.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that the kingdom had yet to bottom out and
more government infrastructure investment was needed to boost
growth.
</P>
<P>
He predicted the country would begin to recover around
mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
He said policy actions should be made to help ease the social
pressures of rising unemployment, while spurring private sector
demand, particularly for the real estate sector, is another
necessity.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a greater government role in
recapitalization of the banking sector. 
</P>
