<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Health Minister Resigns Amid Ructions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian Democratic Union
of Romania, member of Romania's ruling coalition, on Friday
accepted Prime Minister Radu Vasile's request for Health Minister
Franciso Baranyi to step down.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister raised the request on Wednesday after
allegations that Baranyi secretly cooperated in the 1960s with the
then intelligence services.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement between the ruling coalition parties, the
vacancy for the health minister has to be nominated for by the
Hungarian Democratic Union of Romania.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, the Romanian political arena has been
hit by an ongoing political storm, with party leaders,
parliamentary members and ministers accused of collaboration with
intelligence agencies prior to the nation's power handover in
December 1989.
</P>
<P>
Also involved in the ruckus are the National Peasants' Party
and the Democratic Party, both in the ruling coalition, and the
opposition Greater Romania Party.
</P>
<P>
The row emerged when some parliamentary members pressed
parliament to pass a law on access to the former security files.
</P>
<P>
Even before the adoption of the law, some newspapers have
brought some personal files to light, resulting in a number of
political figures, including the health minister, being
implicated.
</P>
<P>
The row has stirred up two different reactions among
the public. Some strongly urge those with an intelligence service
background to quit while others hold that the intelligence agents
under debate were a product of certain historical conditions and
oppose disciplinary action against them.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian intelligence authority has indicated its
determination to step up investigative efforts so as to bring to
court those who stole secret files from the former national
information agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
