<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Sees No Upturn Before Mid-1999: WB Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Thai economy would not start
to recover before the middle of 1999, six months later than
previously predicted by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), a
World Bank official said.
</P>
<P>
Jayasankar Shivakumar, director of the World Bank office in
Thailand, said in remarks published Saturday by The Nation
newspaper that Thailand's economic growth this year would probably
measure minus 5 percent to 8 percent. The World Bank earlier
forecast growth of minus 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and the Thai Finance Ministry previously predicted
economic recovery in the fourth quarter of this year, but that was
unlikely to happen, according to Shivakumar.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the next economic review in August, it is
possible that the World Bank's estimate would drop lower than
minus 5 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ss some Thais are currently negative towards foreign
investment, Shivakumar suggested that Thailand accept foreign
direct investment while setting up mechanisms that would enable
Thais to maintain the right of asset possession.
</P>
<P>
He cited South Korea's move to protect its future national
interests even though it has to sell local assets to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand has no other choice. At present, the country needs
foreign direct investment to recover," he said. "Thus, you have to
make sure that foreign direct investment serves Thailand's
interests."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Thailand should begin working on how to
protect itself from possible future crises.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the recent intervention by the U.S. and
Japan in the currency market was effective, the crisis could
return.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, now in a deep recession, has high interest rates and
a credit crunch which are severely hurting the real sector, while
exports and domestic demand have slumped. According to the World
Bank, the manufacturing index this year is expected to record a
23-percent negative growth. Consumer inflation had already risen
to 10.2 percent by May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
