<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Huge Potential of Children's Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 20 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey on children's
consumer trends in five major Chinese cities indicates a huge
market potential for domestic and imported children's goods.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey by an information company of the State
Statistics Bureau, each one-child family in Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou, Chengdu and Xi'an spends an average of 672 yuan (81
US dollars) each month on children.
</P>
<P>
The monthly spending in Beijing is the highest, reaching 764
yuan (92 US dollars) per child, followed by the 736 yuan (88.7 US
dollars) of Shanghai. And the lowest for children in Xi'an is
merely 207 yuan (24.9 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the above five cities have a total of
5.21 million children aged from one to 12 years old, and their
combined monthly spending top 3.5 billion yuan (421.9 million US
dollars). The survey also reveals that foodstuffs and clothing
make up the bulk of the spending for children, accounting for 66.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The consumption on toys and recreation service comes up the
second, composing 12.3 percent; and that on study-related
commodities makes up 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey also points to the huge potential for imported
children's goods, as 26.4 percent of the respondents voiced their
preference to purchasing foodstuffs imported from overseas and
21.6 percent expressed their interests in imported toys.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, statistics show that the five cities have imported a
total of 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) worth of
children's commodities imported from overseas every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
