<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mullet Bay in Dalian Cleaned up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The once severely-polluted Mullet
Bay of the port city Dalian has been cleaned up thanks to
environmental protection measures.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, the once blue waters of the
Bay was polluted and blocked by silts and industrial wastes,
mainly from a local chemical plant located across the Bay.
</P>
<P>
This not only turned the Bay of the scenic city in northeast
China into a "stink ditch', but also handicapped the launching of
ships of the Dalian New Shipyard, the largest and most important
shipbuilding exporting base in the country.
</P>
<P>
From 1990 to 1996, the shipyard dredged the dock twenty times,
digging up about two million cubic meters of white silt, and
spending more than 22 million yuan (2.7 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Between 1996 and 1997, the shipyard spent another 40 million
yuan (4.8 million US dollars) clearing white silt for 420 meters.
</P>
<P>
In an anti-pollution effort, a 1,924-meter-long dam was erected
to block away the industrial alkali dregs from the 64-year-old
Dalian Chemical Industry Group Ltd Co. on the northern bank of the
bay.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the surrounding water and beaches have returned to
normal and crowds of sea gulls come with the tides, heralding the
improvement of the environment and the gradual revival of the
local biosystem.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
