<HEADLINE> Hubei Province Develops Wudang Mountain Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Wudang Mountain in central China's
Hubei Province attracted more than 500,000 tourists during the
January-May period, up 30 percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The development of infrastructure facilities and development of
tourism resources has helped to transform Wudang Mountain into a
magnet for tourism.
</P>
<P>
Wudang, one of China's Taoist mountains featuring the religion
and philosophy Lao-Tzu introduced in the 6th century B.C., is
located in northwest Hebei, and was listed as a UNESCO World
Cultural Heritage in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Hubei Province has increased inputs to improve the mountain's
infrastructure facilities in recent years. The effort has included
completion of 25-km access road, running tap water to the highest
peak which reaches an elevation of 1,612 meters, installing 3,000
program-controlled telephones in Wudang and constructing a
cableway at a cost of 15 million yuan (1.8 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The province set up the Wudang Mountain Special Economic and
Tourism Zone to accelerate the development of tourism
resources. The overall goal is to transform Wudang Mountain into
an area offering a combination of Taoism culture and beautiful
scenery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
