<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Addresses Mayors Meeting Via Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton warned a
meeting of U.S. mayors on Friday that inequities in schools,
housing and employment cited in a new federal report threaten the
rejuvenation and long-term well-being of their cities.
</P>
<P>
"Our cities are revitalized, energized and back in business,"
Clinton said in an address transmitted by satellite from the White
House to more than 300 city leaders attending the annual U.S.
Conference of Mayors in Reno, Nevada.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot sit back and bask in the glow," the Associated Press
quoted Clinton as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Secretary of Housing and Urban Development
Andrew Cuomo gave the nation's cities a good bill of health, but
said an "opportunity gap" which held down the nation's poorest
citizens poses a constant threat.
</P>
<P>
"This is a midterm report card with an 'A' grade but there is
still homework to be done," Cuomo said of the second annual "State
of the Cities" report released at the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
While crediting the nation's strong five-year economic
performance for the reduction in unemployment that nearly every
major American city enjoys, Cuomo said a discrepancy between the
number of low-skill jobs available and the number of people
seeking them was a cause for worry.
</P>
<P>
At a time when wealth was being created for many, others
remained trapped in a cycle of poverty, poor educational
opportunities and homelessness, Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
"We have more millionaires than at any time in our history,"
Cuomo said. "But an estimated 600,000 Americans still sleep on our
streets every night."
</P>
<P>
Good news for cities abounds in the 75-page report.
</P>
<P>
The economy has produced 16 million new jobs and record low
unemployment, it says. Unemployment in central cities fell to an
average of 5.3 percent early this year from 8.2 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Crime, the age-old bane of city dwelling, has been tamed to a
degree, with violent crime dropping 19 percent in big cities
between 1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
But the report says, poor city residents are being left behind
by growing numbers of middle-class residents. The report says that
since 1970, nearly six million middle-income and affluent families
have left central cities.
</P>
<P>
Poor schools are one of the most frequently cited reasons for
the middle-class flight, according to the study. In 1994 and 1996,
60 percent of children in urban school districts failed to achieve
basic competency on standardized reading and math tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
