<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Marcos' Burial Controversial in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- President-elect Joseph Estrada's
plan to bury the late president Ferdinand Marcos at the heroes'
cemetery in Manila has aroused protests in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said earlier this month that he would allow the remains
of Marcos to be interred in the cemetery which is usually for war
heroes and presidents on July 11 after 9 years of his death.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who will assume the presidency on June 30, urged his
countrymen to forgive their former leader, citing Marcos' role in
fighting the Japanese invaders during the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
"We have to honor and respect a dead man. Let's bury him and
everything with him will be buried", Estrada said, adding there
would be no state honors for Marcos and he would attend the burial
if he has time.
</P>
<P>
However, Estrada's plan drew widespread protests in the
country. Some 28 groups including the church, the business sector,
human rights advocates and professionals recently formed a
coalition and launched a signature drive to voice their anger at
the planned burial of Marcos.
</P>
<P>
Former president Corazon Aquino, who accused Marcos of being a
dictator and masterminding the assassination of her husband,
opposition leader Benigno Aquino, in 1983, led a mass protest
rally near the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Benigno Aquino's death fueled the masses' anger at the Marcos
administration. Three years later, Marcos was ousted in a popular
revolt called "People's Power" in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Marcos fled to Hawaii, the United States, and died there three
years later. Corazon Aquino, who succeeded him, refused to allow
the return of his remains to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Her successor, President Fidel Ramos, allowed the remains of
his distant cousin to be taken to his hometown Batac, Ilocos
Norte, in 1993, but refused to grant him a state funeral. Marcos'
corpse now lies in a refrigerated mausoleum at the Marcos
ancestral home.
</P>
<P>
"The definition of hero and dictator can not be interchanged.
Is it right to honor a dictator who ordered the killing of
thousands of Filipinos, who allowed the torture of those who
opposed him?" Aquino queried, warning she might launch another
"People's Power" if Estrada would not change his mind.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, however, stood firm on his decision. He advised those
opponents to focus on more pressing concerns including crimes,
poverty and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a problem as long as it doesn't violate the
Constitution and the law of the land," he said. The burial did not
mean all the criminal cases filed against the Marcoses would also
be "buried", he added.
</P>
<P>
"Definitely, we will not forget the cases of unexplained wealth
against the Marcoses," he said. "These will continue to be
investigated and prosecuted in the courts."
</P>
<P>
In the past 12 years, a total of 35 civil and criminal cases
had been filed against the Marcoses, but most of them were
dismissed for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
Last January, a division of the Supreme Court ruled that
Imelda, the widow of Marcos, was sentenced to 9 to 12 years'
imprisonment for corruption in an illegal land deal.
</P>
<P>
Imelda, currently on parole, is appealing to the Supreme Court
for reversion. She is not expected to be locked behind the bar.
</P>
<P>
After Imelda's sentence, two Swiss banks returned 300 million
U.S. dollars of Marcos' wealth to the Philippines. Last week, the
banks said they were ready to transfer another 270 million U.S.
dollars to Manila.
</P>
<P>
Despite the protests, Marcos' burial seems not to be affected,
analysts said. His grave in the cemetery is almost ready and
details of the burial are being planned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
