<HEADLINE> Zhengzhou Becomes Regional Commercial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Zhengzhou, the capital city of
central China's Henan Province, has emerged as a commercial center
featuring the most intense and active commercial activities in
central and western China.
</P>
<P>
Zhengzhou's service industry recorded a 1997 value-added of 22
billion yuan (2.65 billion US dollars) of added value, or 39.6
percent of the city's total GDP. The retail sales volume for the
year hit 26.6 billion yuan (3.2 billion US dollars), with the
associated rate of increase elevating Zhengzhou to a leading
position amongst China's commercial centers.
</P>
<P>
Zhengzhou has 120 trade fair markets, with the city's spot
transaction trade volume for trade fairs and markets approaching
100 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
A number of markets, including the clothing, footwear and
building materials markets, enjoy annual trade volumes reaching
several billion yuan. Related markets have emerged as nationwide
pillars in their respective sectors.
</P>
<P>
The city has attempted to remain apace of commercial
development by reinforcing infrastructure construction such as
railways, airports and transport facilities and improving urban
telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, approximate 10,000 domestic and overseas commercial
organizations have opened offices and branches in Zhengzhou, and
the city hosts dozens of national and regional trade fairs and
exhibitions each year. The city's daily floating population
averages more than 600,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Expects Little Change in Oil Prices by OPEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The meeting of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) scheduled for next week in
Vienna will not change in any major way the oil prices
performance, a leading Venezuelan petrol businessman said.
</P>
<P>
Luis Guisti, president of Petroleos de Venezuela, told the "El
Nacional" newspaper that the market would not necessarily react
to the OPEC meeting, but would be effected by seasonal changes in
the the third and fourth quarters of this year."
</P>
<P>
"We are entering a different season of the year and this will
affect the prices," he predicted.
</P>
<P>
Guisti said the benchmark West Texas Intermediate (WTI) crude,
now over 15.40 U.S. dollars per barrel, would have to reach 17
dollars achieve the provisions stated in Venezuela's national
budget.
</P>
<P>
"If the WTI price reaches that level, we will easily achieve
the 13 dollars for the Venezuelan basket," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Guisti said he expected the long-awaited recovery to come after
mid-year. The second quarter of the year, which historically was
the worst, was about to finish. Venezuela had large stocks of
oil, and that makes it necessary to wait for later in the year
year," he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said factors deciding oil prices included Germany's
purchases to supply its strategic reserves, and the suspension of
production for maintenance in the North Sea in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
