<HEADLINE> Mercosur Opens Anti-Drug Trafficking Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Mercosur opened its first
meeting Friday on the prevention and elimination of drug
trafficking and connected crimes.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the meeting, Argentine minister in charge of
anti-drug addiction and drug trafficking Eduardo Amadeo called on
his Mercosur counterparts to strengthen cooperation on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Amadeo expressed his desire for "the creation of a common
language in this struggle for life," which was the war against
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The meeting stressed the need to stop money laundering and
control chemicals for the manufacturing of drugs and illicit
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed the possibility of creating a
permanent consultation forum in the region for the start of joint
activities in the war against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, or Southern Common Market, is the largest commercial
trade bloc in South America, grouping Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay,
and Paraguay, with Chile and Bolivia as associate members. 
</P>
