<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Eases Bank Capital Requirements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- In another concerted effort to
speed up the restructuring process of Indonesia's ailing banking
industry, the government eased bank capital requirements Friday,
local press Saturday quoted a minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Existing banks were no longer required to have a minimum
paid-up capital of 250 billion rupiah (25 million U.S. dollars) by
the end of this year, Minister of Finance Bambang Subianto said.
</P>
<P>
"Only new banks are now obliged to meet this capital
requirement," Bambang told reporters after meeting with President
B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to force ailing banks to merge, Indonesia set
tough minimum paid-up capital requirements of between 1 trillion
rupiah (100 million U.S. dollars) and 2 trillion rupiah (200
million U.S. dollars) last January.
</P>
<P>
But the 1 trillion rupiah requirement was later slashed down to
250 billion rupiah following strong objections from the banking
community and the deadline for the 250 billion rupiah requirement
was extended to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Bambang urged owners of the country's ailing banks to
accelerate the process of recapitalizing their institutions to
meet the capital requirements.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the capital adequacy ratio (CAR) for
banks was also lowered so that they were now required to fulfill a
minimum CAR of only 4 percent by the end of 1998, 8 percent in
1999 and 10 percent by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The previous CAR requirements were 8 percent by the end of this
year, 10 percent by the end of next year and 12 percent by the end
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of the overall effort to revive the economy and
the banking sector in particular," the minister explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0199 </DOCNO>
