<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKFA "Painful" of Players Involved in Match-fixing Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Football
Association (HKFA) said in a statement here on Friday that it felt
"painful" to the allegations against the Hong Kong Team players
and the confession of one of them for being involved in the
match-fixing scandal.
</P>
<P>
"We are ever more disappointed for such incident happened to
the Hong Kong Team," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"It has been our motives to develop and promote the game in
Hong Kong and emphasis is particularly placed on the set-up and
training of the representative sides," as they represent Hong
Kong, which has become a special administrative region of China
since July last year, in international tournaments.
</P>
<P>
"Their performance and achievement directly relate to the image
of Hong Kong football," it said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the news broke over the weekend, HKFA's president
Timothy Fok contacted FIFA President-elected Sepp Blatter, saying
that HKFA backs his proposal for a football school to teach just
skills but also ethics. HKFA concurs with the FIFA chief, who had
said football was more than a game and was a social obligation,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
HKFA believes something positive can be made of something so
negative and it must take this chance to review the structure of
the game, it continued.
</P>
<P>
"We reiterate our position against the influence of match
results by dishonest means as well as our determination to prevent
 similar incidents from happening again," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The game's local governing body will set up an ad hoc working
party to deal with the players concerned and prudently study and
discuss measures to avoid the reoccurrence of such unhappy
incident," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Six local senior division players were arrested last week by
Hong Kong's Independent Commission Against Corruption (ICAC)
following allegations that they had received bribes before making
the Hong Kong team lose two goals in a World Cup Asian Preliminary
Round Group 6 match on March 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Chan Tsz-kong, one of the players arrested, pleaded guilty to
conspiracy at a court hearing here on Friday, to fix the result of
the match so as to win for himself and others 200,000 HK dollars
(25,600 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
