<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anhui Province Reports Remarkable Agricultural Productivity Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The comprehensive agricultural
productivity of east China's Anhui Province, which played an
important symbolic role in China's market-oriented reforms, has
improved significantly in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
As the place where the household responsibility system was
initiated in 1978, Anhui now has become a major producer
of food grain, cotton edible oil, among other things.
</P>
<P>
Anhui's grain output reached 28 billion kg last year, a surge
of 13.7 billion kg from 1978. Also last year, Anhui's cotton
output reached 300,00 tons, a rise of 1.6 times over the 1978
figure, edible oil output hit 2.05 million tons, up 5.3 times,
meat output totaled 2.77 million tons, up 4.6 times, and aquatic
products reached 1.35 tons, up 24.5 times.
</P>
<P>
In the last ten years, Anhui sold an average of nine billion kg
of commodity grain each year, with 2.5 billion sold to other parts
of China.
</P>
<P>
Officials are optimistic about further increases in Anhui's
agricultural production, as some 2.6 million ha of low-yielding
farmland still has great potential in productivity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Professional Footballer Involved in Match-fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's professional
football player Chan Tsz-kong on Friday pleaded guilty to
conspiracy at the Eastern Court here for fixing the result of
last years World Cup quarlifying match against Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Chan, 26, was one of the six local professional footballers
arrested here last week by Hong Kong's Independent Commission
Against Corruption (ICAC) in its investigation into an illegal
match betting syndicate allegedly facilitated by corruption.
</P>
<P>
Chan, a member of the Hong Kong Special Administration Region
(SAR) Team at last year's World Cup Asian Zone qualifying
tournament, admitted one count of conspiring with the team's
goalkeeper Lok Kar-win and others to fix the result of a March 9,
1997 match against Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the match, Chan, Lok and two other members of
the team decided they should only cause the team to lose two goals
in order not to arouse suspicion. Chan approached to another
teammate who agreed to join the scheme. Thailand subsequently won
the match 2-0.
</P>
<P>
Chan later obtained 200,000 HK dollars (25,600 U.S. dollars)
from a bookmaker for himself and others involved in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Magistrater Garry Tallentire adjourned sentencing until next
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
