<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Torrential Rains Hit Zhejiang Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Some areas of east China's
Zhejiang Province have been affected by a rain spell in the past
three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains have stormed the cities of Quzhou, Lanxi,
Jiande and Jinhua, and Lishui Prefecture in western Zhejiang since
the entry of what is called the plum rain season on the Chinese
lunar calender on June 16. The daily rainfall exceeded 150 mm in
some of these places and the water flow at part of the Qiantang
River reached the maximum of 9,000 cubic meters each second.
</P>
<P>
In Qingyuan, Longquan and Pan'an, standing crops have been
flattened and irrigation networks and water conservancy facilities
have been wrecked or damaged to varying extent.
</P>
<P>
Heavy or torrential rains will continue in Zhejiang Province in
the near future, according to meteorological forecasts. To ensure
safety, the Hangzhou navigation authorities have declared
first-rate flood control on the Qiantang River and banned vessels
on the upper stream from entering the river.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
