<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Restraint in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Friday appealed again to parties to the Cyprus dispute to
abstain from any action to increase tension on the island.
</P>
<P>
His remarks appeared in a statement made by his spokesman which
said, "In recent days, there have been signs of increased military
activity in Cyprus and in the region."
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general reiterates the appeal he made in his
good offices report of June 16 and trusts that all parties
involved will abstain from any action which could add to the
tension," it said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since Turkish troops took over the
northern third of the island in 1974 following a failed pro-Athens
coup in Nicosia, the capital.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been mounting since early last year when Cyprus
ordered the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft misslies, due to be
delivered later this year. Turkey has threatened to use all means
to block their deployment.
</P>
<P>
Turkey sent six F-16 fighters to the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
northern Cyprus Thursday in retaliation for the landing of six
Greek warplanes in the Greek Cyprus-controlled south earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the U.N. Security Council, Annan said Tuesday
that his special adviser on Cyprus intends to visit the island in
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret at the failure of his efforts to bring the
concerned parties to direct negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Cut to Go On in Moldova </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Power cut is to go on in the
Republic of Moldova because Ukraine stopped supplying electricity
while Russia reduced its gas supply in half to Moldova, the
Moldovan BASA-Press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Moldtranselectro, which is dealing with delivery
of electric energy to the distributing agencies, switched off in
these days the electricity around Moldova following the recent cut
of gas delivery by Russia, Moldtranselectro director Mihail
Cebotari said.
</P>
<P>
Cebotari said that the company will continue to cut off users
from the grids unless the government presents to Russia's gas
monopoly Gazprom a plan of debt repayment.
</P>
<P>
Gazprom, Moldova's major source of energy, cut its gas supply
in half in a bid to press for an immediate payment of the 200
million dollar gas dues. The move has affected the operation of
the leading power plant in Moldova, which provides 80 percent of
the country's electricity.
</P>
<P>
According to Cebotari, Moldovan users were supplied only 80
percent of their electricity consumption in the first five months
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Power shortages in Moldova have crippled government
institutions, hospitals, banks, telecommunication services and
public transportation.
</P>
<P>
Electricity was cut off in half of the capital city of
Chisinau, including the downtown with its governmental buildings
and parliament, for several hours Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
