<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Continues to Criticize Republicans Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday described Republican attempts to work out a slimmed-down
anti-smoking legislation a "charade" and nothing but a rush for
political "cover."
</P>
<P>
Clinton accused the Republicans of playing political games to
protect the tobacco industry while ignoring the health threat to
children.
</P>
<P>
Since Wednesday's defeat of a comprehensive tobacco bill
sponsored by Republican Senator John McCain in the Senate, there
have been reports that Congress is working on a narrowly focused
bill.
</P>
<P>
"I'm against anything that provides no lifesaving to kids and
is designed to save the political life of the people who vote for
it, to provide cover, but won't save the lives of the children,"
Clinton said. "I don't see why we should participate in a
charade."
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the House of Representatives Newt Gingrich said
Thursday that next week he would propose a slimmed-down bill
focused on discouraging children from smoking by more closely
regulating access to cigarettes rather than raising the per-pack
price.
</P>
<P>
The McCain bill that Clinton supported would have raised the
price by at least 1.10 dollar a package over five years. It also
would have allowed the Food and Drug Administration to regulate
cigarette advertising and marketing and would have forced the
tobacco companies to pay heavy penalties if the level of teen
smoking did not fall to specific level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia: Humanitarian Program for Iraq, Temporary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The humanitarian program
for Iraq is a temporary measure, and permanent measures for the
Iraqi people could only be taken after the sanctions against the
country were lifted, Russia's Ambassador to the United Nations
Sergey Lavrov stressed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lavrov made the remarks after the United Nations Security
Council adopted a resolution which authorized Iraq to import 300
million U.S. dollars worth of oil equipment and spare parts to
upgrade its capacity of oil export. The resolution also noted that
Iraq's new food distribution plan approved by the U.N.
secretary-general on May 29, 1998 would not automatically be
rewritten every six months but would continue unless the U.N.
secretary-general approved changes.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the council after it voted on the resolution, Lavrov
said it was important to ensure that the resolution did not change
existing procedures for approving the distribution plan.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that for each new phase of the operation,
the Iraq government must submit a draft for a new plan to be
approved by the U.N. secretary-general, and that procedure stemmed
from the resolution just unanimously adopted by the council.
</P>
<P>
He said there was a new spirit of cooperation that existed
between Iraq and the United Nations due to the U.N.
secretary-general's last visit to Iraq, and the speeding up of
United Nations humanitarian operation in Iraq required the
adoption of urgent measures to rehabilitate the Iraqi oil industry.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador added that work must be done in accordance with
Security resolution 1153 of 1998 and the distribution plan
approved by the U.N. chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
