<HEADLINE> China: Oil-for-Food Program, Temporary Arrangement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The "oil-for-food" program
is a provisional and temporary arrangement to meet the
humanitarian needs in Iraq, Chinese Permanent Representative to
the United Nations Qin Huasun stressed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin was responding to a resolution of the Security
Council of the United Nations which was adopted Friday morning.
The resolution allowed Iraq to import 300 million U.S. dollars
worth of oil equipment and spare parts. At the same time, the
resolution noted that Iraq's new food distribution plan approved
by the U.N. secretary-general on My 29, 1998 would not
automatically be rewritten every six months but would continue
unless the U.N. secretary-general approved changes.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the council before it began to vote on the
resolution, Qin said, "The oil-for-food program should not be a
substitute for or a means of delaying the lifting of sanctions on
Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"The current draft before the council was only a technical
resolution and some parts of it were not necessary," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
"However, in order to speed the import of equipment as soon as
possible, China will support the resolution, and the import of
spare parts should be realized as soon as possible," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
