<DOCNO> XIE19980620.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania, Turkey to Strengthen Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 19 (Xinhua) - Turkish investors don't need the
green light of the International Monetary Fund or other world
finance bodies to come to Romania, visiting Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz told businessmen Friday in Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
Mesut Yilmaz, who, together with his Romanian counterpart Radu
Vasile, had a meeting with local and foreign businessmen in
Bucharest, also said the interest of the Turkish investors in
Romania is grounded on the friendship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the "excellent" bilateral relations, the Turkish
prime minister showed that his country sees Romania as a partner
"for strengthening cooperation in the Balkans and Europe." "It's
time for Turkish and Romanian businessmen to expand to third
markets," he said, adding that the Turkish government's message to
investors is: "Turkey will strengthen cooperation with Romania."
</P>
<P>
In turn, Radu Vasile thanked foreign businessmen in general and
Turkish ones in particular for having ignored the problems caused
by the transition process and accepted Romania as "a country with
great potential."
</P>
<P>
He sent to Turkish businessmen the Romanian government's
message: "Keep on doing business in Romania and we shall secure
the necessary framework so that your benefits and the benefits to
Romania will be mutually advantageous."
</P>
<P>
Mesut Yilmaz ended his two-day visit to Romania Thursday
evening. He is the first prime minister of Turkey who visited
Romania after a 12-year break-off. Mesut Yilmaz was accompanied by
many businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a very important partner of Romania in the economic
domain. The volume of bilateral trade was 567 million U.S. dollars
in 1997, and is expected to reach 1 billion this year. Turkey is
at the same time among the most important investors in Romania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
